Viotto awakens on a bed staring at an unfamiliar ceiling.

I lay there silently for a few moments, before tears start running down my face. I can't do anything to stop them. Why doesn't it ever end? Why can I not stop losing them? The moment just replays in my head, over and over again. The most banal form of grief. And I can't even stand that.

It begins to feel like something is moving around inside of me, some kind of snake twisting itself back and forth just underneath my skin. But moving my arm to swat at it would be more effort than it's worth.
But there's something shifting inside my head, too, and I can do much less to stop myself from confronting that.

It's like, before... the back half of my brain was filled with TV static, and the front half was habitable. And now, they've suddenly switched. The front half is unbearable to put myself into. And I keep trying to drag myself to the back, this new space I have to live in, but... there's some kind of intense homesickness I now have for the front. I know I can't survive there, not at the moment. But I feel as if my blood has stopped flowing, and there's an ice bath sitting just next to me, ready to restart the circulation. That disgusting pull of the shock.
I can only miss a state of mind, and nothing more specific.
This happens.
Indeed, it keeps happening.
What do you want from me?
Even more?

Conversation becomes audible from outside the room.

Viotto isn’t talking to anyone. No one wants anything from him. I guess his being here means at least one person does, but whatever.
I scream, "What do you even want to know?!" loud enough for anybody outside to hear me.
A few seconds later, there’s a knock at the door.
"Come in," I whisper, hoping they don't hear.
After a bit, they open the door. ((a moment))
#viotto-swansong-reaction

Joliene wakes up on Earth. She would immediately be able to tell that’s where she is because of her body, but it also becomes clear that this is a room of a similar sort to the one she first awoke on Earth in.

That's interesting. Joliene doesn't remember falling asleep.

She checks to see if her PDA is on her, or if the room has anything of interest inside it.
Her PDA is on her. The room has an empty bookshelf in it. It isn’t particularly decorated. There is a single door and no windows.
She leaves the only way she can, then.

The room she exits into is dodecagonal, but this probably isn’t the first detail that would strike her.

It’s large, and brightly decorated, as though for a party. A banner hanging from the ceiling reads:

> TAP Q&A

Hanging slightly lower is a second banner, reading

> (The Antarctica Project Question And Answers)

There’s a table with some refreshments available. Four poles are set up in the room with ropes tied between them to create an enclosed square. 

And in the center of the room, sitting on a folding chair, disheveled, unshaven, is who Joliene would recognize as PH, the project head. He’s wearing what appears to be a bathrobe.

He looks up as you approach.

Ah.

Joliene carefully steps closer to PH, and by proxy, the rest of the room’s setpieces. “Hello. How long has it been since we spoke directly like this?” She looks over the room again, to make sure she and PH are the only ones here.

“For me? …Could be a year at this point. It is difficult to keep track. I couldn’t say with confidence how long it’s been for you.” He smiles looking at you. It is an expression that does not feel remotely fitting on him.
"...I see." She chooses not to inquire further as to what was meant by this. "It must be a special occasion."
“Yes. The Antarctica Project is over. This is a… post-mortem, perhaps.”
She blinks. "Really? Just like that?"
“Yes. Just like that. It was never supposed to be something with a glamorous showstopper of an ending. Though I suppose my counterpart on the other side had plans of his own.” He sighs.
"...Did something happen that I should be aware of?" She, once again, looks around to check if they're alone.
There is no one currently in this room aside from the two of them. There’s also a monitor, but that doesn’t count as a person. And everything mentioned prior within the room.
“You would know better than I what exactly has transpired in Arctica.”
One of the doors other than the one Joliene entered from has someone screaming an incoherent question audibly from behind it. PH gazes towards that one.

"Well, yes, but..."

She cuts herself off, and looks at the door as well.
“An unpleasant awakening for him, I suppose.”
"Mm."
He walks over to this door and knocks on it.
She waits and watches.
After a little while, he opens the door. ((making channel))
#viotto-swansong-reaction

Viotto is in a bed. A man he does not recognize opens the door, with a woman he doesn’t recognize nearby.

“Are you alright, Mr. Entenmann?” The man.

"As alright as I've ever been... HA!" 
I try my hardest to get up in any form resembling dramatism, but only manage to pull myself into a sitting position in a motion that gives off the impression of a sick, dying man. The laugh comes out as more of a sob.
I lean over with my head in my hands, still trying to ignore the movements of the snake.
Joliene watches this silently, looking through the doorframe from a distance.
I eye her through the gaps in my fingers. She doesn't seem familiar, but I'm not reliable on that front.
“I see.” He nods. “I would prefer not to converse through a doorway. Unless you miraculously have zero things to say to me, I suppose.”
“I am the… closest thing left to a man behind The Antarctica Project. The ‘Project Head’. My name is Zaquera Culbasko. It is a pleasure to make your acquaintance.” He nods solemnly.
Hm? Does this man not know who the Project Head is? Then why would he...
"And what happened to all the others? Dead, like my friend? Like everybody?"
"Did you even know Sheeval?"

“Mr. Deltent was a… close friend of mine.” His neutral expression falters. “I do not know what happened to him as of yet. Beyond that it was a tragedy, of course. …The police have blamed *you* as the culprit.”
He glares briefly.
“…But I do not particularly buy that.”

He sighs. “If by ‘all the others’ you mean your fellow participants, then no, they are not dead. I merely chose to bring the three of you here before everyone else.”
"...Can you tell us why?" she finally asks.
"I don't know of any other participants. I meant that you said you were the highest person remaining. What happened to the implied others?"
I raise my head, feeling slightly better from the conversation about nothing.

“You would not know, Joliene… your group was small and remained quite amicable. But it is my understanding that the last time the Earth participants were amassed, they squabbled and wasted all of their time doing nothing. I wanted those I judged the most reasonable a moment to themselves before bringing mayhem potentially *worse* in scope.”

He returns to addressing Viotto. “That is… a long story. They are not all dead, no.”
"I see." She doesn't say anything else for now.
"...who is the third?"

“That would be —”

One of the other doors opens. A man Joliene does not know exits and looks around. 

“…Klaud Reaction. There we are.”
“You’re…” Klaud trails off.
“Zaquera Culbasko.” Zaquera. “…Now we can begin proper. Welcome to the Q&A session.”
Joliene looks silently at the new man.
I struggle to my feet, head slowly to Klaud and attempt to hug him.
“Uh….” Klaud exists in this hug limply. “Hello, Viotto. Good to see you’re okay.”
"You too. Although, don't think I've forgotten the accusation of homosexuality." I break away and lower myself back onto the bed.
"What are your plans for us, Zack?"
“My plans are over.” Zaquera. “It’s over. The Antarctica Project is over.”
Klaud sighs. “…Where is this?”
“We’re in Antarctica.” Zaquera.
"...Do you understand why the project is over?"
“It was always supposed to end after a predefined amount of swaps. …Even if the way that transferring happened ended up falling apart a bit.” Zaquera explains.
“Was there always a set criteria that triggered the swaps? I always assumed that it happened when I fell asleep, but I don’t remember anything like that happening this last time.”
"Maybe it happens when I fall asleep, instead of you. Whatever it is."

“There was not. It was based on a timer, but… a timer often difficult to directly control or alter. Virtos seemed to be under the impression at first that people needed to be asleep for it to work, though. There must have been some miscommunication.”

"...I see."

Joliene turns to the refreshment table again. She's trying to determine if there's anything alcoholic being offered.
There is.
She takes some of that.
Why would there be a refreshment table? What kind of place is this?
Am I even in a proper building? What's the temperature like in here?
It’s average room temperature.
“Viotto. I am… not very adept. At understanding the emotions of others. But you seem troubled.” Zaquera averts his eyes. “…I am sorry for whatever part I played in that.”
I consider laughing again, but don't. "I have no idea what the scope of this project is. Did you play any part in it? How would you expect me to know, or even to guess?"

"I suppose in a broad sense, you WERE responsible, no matter what you did. You triggered the events that led everyone to where they are now. But so did many, many others. There is no real personal responsibility in something like that, as you should know by now."
"You were not there to do anything. At least, that is my belief."

“I see.” He nods. “This is certainly a perspective one could have. And yet, are there not positive obligations? Consider the trolley problem. An ethical conundrum that nonetheless has an overwhelming consensus. To allow more people to die via deliberate inaction is wrong. Would you disagree with this more popular opinion?”
"If you acted deliberately to allow this to happen, then it would only be a contradiction of my statement that you were not there to help."
"I have no comment on the philosophical problem."

“I suppose. And yet quantifying that line could be blurry. How many steps ahead do you need to consider your actions? Asimov once wrote a story wherein robots were programmed to be unable to do harm, but permitted to do harm by inaction. This speculatively allowed for absurd results, such as being capable of dropping something heavy to crush a person to death with the reasoning that their ability to catch it before that prevents the act from inherently being a harmful one. …And then they simply don’t catch it.”
He clears his throat. “I’m not considering this directly analogous. I don’t know what it is that happened to you, after all. And nothing I have done regarding this project is quite so blunt or… close-quarters. Yet any suffering you have endured as a result of this project… well, I believe culpability is a gray area. Perception is reality. That’s how it goes.” He shrugs. 
“In my experience, as one ages, the amount of obligations one has and harm via inaction one is capable of grows without end. At some point… it all starts to…”

He stops in his tracks, as though forgetting a word.
Joliene takes a swig.
"If you believe that perception is reality, then do you find yourself exonerated from any wrongdoing by the fact that I haven't blamed you yet? Is that the point of this little diatribe?"

"I'm older than you. And yet, I cannot relate to what you're saying whatsoever. I've never felt that the amount of harm I'm capable of via inaction has grown, for the simple reason that the amount of action I'm capable of taking has always stayed relatively the same. Whatever concessions I make morally, I must have always made. That's what got me where I am. That's what got everyone where they are. That's what I'm to blame for."

“…Are you older than me…? …I guess you probably are. Slightly.” He sighs. This is definitely an older man, though.
“I can’t agree with you at all. Though I suppose we’ve lived different lives. To my understanding, your capacity for action has indeed remained unchanged for a lengthy period.”
"Then maybe you should tie it to power instead of age."

“A fair point. I did not consider the distinction there. …Though this relates to something else, about consequences. Even as people agree on some fundamental wrongs, the projection of mindset a person performs unconsciously can lead to unpredicted suffering.” He keeps fucking talking. “I spent my youth in squalor. To me, a childhood of luxury and comfort would have been endlessly preferable. Paradisian. But that clearly isn’t enough for all humans.”
"Sorry. Does any of this tie back into the project?"
“Yes.”

"I don't think saying that you would have liked to be rich is some novel, subversive observation. Nor do I understand how it relates to the thing you said beforehand. You... project a performed mindset... unconsciously? I understand how a performance can be unconscious, and I understand an unconscious mindset, but to be frank, if you're performing a mindset, it has to be at least somewhat in-mind. If all of this is happening without your knowledge, then your entire person has been denied free will. It sounds absurd for the sake of nihilism."
"And we should get back to the topic at hand, yes."
"Good point... girl."
"Mm. Joliene."
"Yes."
"I suppose you would be Viotto, if I have all my information in order."

“All mindsets are performed. Otherwise, they would not exist at all.” What? What is he fucking talking about? What?
“What about TAP do you want to discuss?”

"There's, um..." Joliene retrieves her PDA, and taps at it a couple times, contemplative.

"What's the deal with my body?"
I turn to her sadly. "Good question. What is the deal with it?"
I wish the conversation about mindsets could have gone on for longer. I had an interesting response, possibly.
But everyone deserves a turn.

“Well, there’s the obvious of providing you an opportunity to walk, and the problems your standard appearance would have presented on earth. I believe the other end had measures set up for it anyone’s physical characteristics made them stand out excessively in Arctica, but that didn’t end up becoming relevant.”
He gestures vaguely with his free hand while adjusting his glasses. “I…I’m stalling. The real question there is why we even had a fully intact human body for someone to inhabit.”
He looks down. “…There was an attempt to bring back someone whose life had ended. It involved nearly perfectly recreating her body. It did not work.”

"And yet it worked well enough for a still-living consciousness to inhabit it instead?"

She pauses for just a moment. "Were you aiming to revive this woman in particular, or could it have been anyone?"

“Just one person. …The mechanics of transferring consciousness are an order of magnitude simpler than recreating it. The former was solved quite some time ago. Voreverl is living proof of that. The latter has… only produced errors.”
"Because resurrection is an affront to God and nature. If sin could be undone, there would be no functional mechanic of a soul."
"That seems clear. I don't know why you would even consider it worth attempting."

"...I see. That's all on that front, then." Once again, her attention turns to her PDA. "What is the goal of The Antarctica Project? There are some things I can... intuit. Or, I can at least try to. I assume the end goal wasn't as simple as testing the mechanics of a body swap, or the transfer of consciousnesses between worlds. Is it related to the manner in which these two worlds were linked? And the reason Earth and Arctica share a language? And on that note, uh... who invented the computer?"
“Souls do not exist on Earth. Not for most practical purposes.” Zaquera says this like it’s a normal statement.
“…They do.” Klaud mutters.
"How could they exist for *some* practical purposes, but not all? Your belief is nonsensical..."
"Thank you, Klaud. Sincerely."
"I feel comforted to have alike company in this room."
“People can have their own beliefs. Especially when they are faith based and thus unfalsifiable. But there is an objectively verifiable sense of a soul, and it does not exist here.”
“Nothing but matter.” He takes out and checks a pocketwatch.

He puts it back away. “Sorry, you asked some questions, Joliene. The purpose of the Project… to be honest, some of the time I’ve asked myself that very question. It’s felt like it exists simply to exist. But ultimately, at its conception, it involves preventing entropic decay via facilitating enhanced and deliberately placed perception that validates and ensures the legitimate existence of both Earth and Arctica.”

I catch one of the words. "The idea that perception exists, and has any measurable effect, is based on faith, Zack. Light hitting an eye, triggering a neuron, is no different from any other material, any other matter. What do you have to say to that?"
“Exactly.”
“My name is not Zack, also, but that is unimportant.”
"I was abbreviating."
"You can call me Vio, if you so wish."
"It's only fair."
“That is fine.”

"I agree that I don't see the link between those from Arctica observing Earth preventing its eventual decay, if I'm interpreting your explanation correctly. Even if there were some link between observation and each world's safety, they're already continuously being observed by their many natives."
"I can confirm that I look at the Earth relatively often. It does raise the question of whether it has to be the actual dirt and soil, or whether you could just look at a building, I suppose."

“That is true. An unobserved world would have fared far worse. …I suppose it very well wouldn’t exist at all, for our practical purposes.” He shakes his head. “I should mention that I use ‘Earth’ and ‘Arctica’ as standins for ‘the entire plane of existence wherein those places reside’. I am speaking of our entire reality, not the sun having one less planet. It’s just that Earth is, for us on it, obviously the most important and central aspect of reality.”
“The right man in the wrong place can make all the difference. It was imperative to provide recognition of Arctica *from Earth*, and vice versa.”
"But why?"
"Exactly - why? It seems undeniably egotistical. Our planet occupies no special place in creation."
"You yourself admit it, and yet you outline a necessary separation."
"Ostensibly necessary, I should say."

“Because perception affects reality, and the volatility of both our worlds is caused by the other. …Viotto is asking a different — more semantic — question, I think, to which my answer would simply be the existence of life that can observe at all is effectively exclusive to Earth.”
"Arcticans - if such a divisible group exists - do not have souls? Is that, perhaps, what you are saying?"

“No. I was speaking within the context of the universe Earth is in. I am not one to make such judgments. Due to magic, souls can be verified for them, within the context of their own world. But that is besides the point.”

A monitor in the other room, which I guess they’re half in because they’re still conversing through Viotto’s fucking doorway, lights up. It displays an emoticon styled face. A voice can be heard, clearly through a speaker. 
“There is no objective basis to consider Arcticans ‘life’ in the way it is conceived here.”

Klaud’s eyes light up with recognition. “…It’s good to see you. Or, well… you know.”

“Likewise.” Monitor voice. “I did not mean to eavesdrop, I simply didn’t want to overwhelm people with information without something to contribute.”

Zaquera looks vaguely annoyed at the interruption, but nods. “That is true.”
Joliene looks at the monitor. "...What?"
I lean over to peer into the other room.
"I thought there were only the three of us?"

The other room is equipped for a celebration or party of some sort. There are refreshments, banners reading ‘TAP Q&A’ along with a clarification of what that stands for, and a smaller square area enclosed by rope. 

“This is an… assistive presence in TAP.” Zaquera gestures to the monitor also in the room. “Jeh, for those already loosely aware. Short for Jehorvand, but he isn’t really the same as that.”

“Hello!” Jeh, apparently. “Congratulations to you all on completing The Antarctica Project.”

“I thought you were against the project. Or mixed on it.” Klaud.

“Congratulations are in order nonetheless. I appreciate the time all of you have invested into this.” Jeh.

“Against it…? Has everyone forsaken me?” Zaquera holds his head.

“I would never betray you.” Jeh.

“Tch.” Zaquera.
“There are three participants, and me.” Zaquera clarifies. “Jeh is not a participant. Nor is he human.”
What does the banner say it stands for? Just to be sure.
‘The Antarctica Project Questions And Answers’
Hm.
"Can I ask what you meant by Jeh not being the same as his full name?"
"...This... still doesn't feel real, somehow. None of this does."
"It was confusingly worded."
"I understand why you feel that way."
"No, I don't think you do."
"Why deny me this?"
"Agh. I really have appreciated the presence of you all here, but this is getting to be a burden on me. I'd just like to go to the next place, please. Zack?"

“It’s understandable. Questioning reality is both a necessity as well as the enemy here. You may parse all of this however you wish. …Jehorvand refers to a program created decades ago. Also, for what it’s worth, the man who invented the computer is Mohammad Avdol. Though in some sense, no one ever invented the computer.”
He turns to Viotto. “Next place?”
"...I speak objectively. A lot of things have happened before this point you have no way of knowing about."
"Emotion is universal. A father's grief is comparable to a sister's, or a child's. Somebody will always understand."
"I disagree."
"Specifics don't matter as much as you might think. And yes, I'd like to move on, Zach."

“All of you will be provided transportation back to wherever you consider home, but logistically, that will only occur after everyone is present and accounted for. There are other rooms in this facility if you are looking for something. …Also, we’ve rounded up the various stragglers affected by this project and brought them here. They are elsewhere in the building. This includes those companions you were somehow made to bring with you on transfers as well as a select few people who have somehow made the shift using the devices allocated to deceased participants.”

“Ah. That’s good.” Klaud sighs in relief. “Martin’s okay, then.”

“Yes.” Zaquera nods.
"...Zita?"
“I believe so. I don’t really know all their names.”
"Is- is that a good idea?"
“What do you mean by that?”
"...no, no. It's nothing. Never mind. The last thing I remember before the transfer, she was in rather an affected state. I'm sure she would have gotten over it by now."
"What if I don't consider anywhere home?"

"Is that selection automated as well? So much left up to the machines... electricity, deciding the course of our lives. It's so ironically genius, so well-considered, only some higher power could have envisioned it so perfectly. Hah!"

“With proper communication, everyone understood this was likely in their best interest, and cooperated. Those from Arctica had no other home and wanted answers themselves. Those from Earth varied from fugitives to those legally dead to… Rene.” Zaquera sighs.
“We were going to default to France, after having sorted out the legal issues. If you’d prefer something else, that can be arranged.”
"You cannot transport me to an entire country. Will I be dropped at the first dock available?"
"You are being awfully pedantic, no?"
Joliene drinks a bit more.
“I don’t know where you’re from. I avoid minute details. Micromanagement is generally a waste of time.”

“…You ripped me away from my normal life and I still barely understand why.” Klaud mutters.

“I apologize that the explanation is not sufficiently int— clear.” Zaquera.
“How were the participants selected? Was it complete chance? Are some individuals more suited to observing the opposite world than others?”
"If you've avoided the detail of where I'm going, will it be selected at random? What does that mean?"
"You're answering none of our questions. It's bordering on absurdity."

“Virtos selected the participants in Arctica personally. I don’t know his reasons. For Earth, it was indeed done - mostly - algorithmically, to maximize the efficacy of this perception.”

“This happens to have prioritized people with incredibly warped or deluded worldviews.” Jeh interrupts.

Zaquera sighs. “…Sure.”
"You need to be more open for this to work."
“I am answering all of them. If you do not want to go anywhere you will not be taken anywhere. It’s as simple as that.” He snaps, annoyed.
"I want to go to the next place, I told you. That's always been arranged. What's so different about this time?"
"I'm not satisfied with a vague return to sender. I hope you understand why."
“There is no next place. The project is over. I do not understand your language.”
“This is the end, apparently. I don’t see why you’re in such a rush to leave. I doubt you will get an opportunity like this again.”
She fingers at her device with her free hand.
"An opportunity? An opportunity to what? Chat up a brick wall and a computer? What chance do I have in this place? What opportunity?"

“Would thinking of it as a puzzle help you? I can tell you’re discontent with the project, but don’t you want to piece together the reason for your being here? Know why this project, or your opposite world, exists at all? You’re quite old, and from the sound of things, don’t have much of anything to return to. Are you just being contrarian for the sake of contrarianism? Or is there a better reason you’re in such a rush?”

"No, it wouldn't. Why would I want it to be a puzzle? I want it to be solved! It should be a done deal, a final conclusion! It's supposedly over! But we both know, deep down, that isn't true. No, this is no puzzle, girl. This is a test. And you're failing it. I'm not a contrarian. I'm a problem-solver."

"Zack, just tell us what we need to do. Send me where I need to go. It's not Unspecified, France, or I would be there. There would be no need for this farce. It's certainly not me staying here in Antarctica. I have somewhere to be, so let's cut to the chase. I need to be there, now."
((End session))

"You are free to head out of this room, if you wish." Zaquera mutters dismissively.

Klaud checks his PDA.
Joliene glances around uncomfortably.
(( @Viotto Entenmann bwaaaaa (?)))
((sorrryyy I didn't know))
((give me a minute))
"And what would be outside? A snowstorm, ready to end my life? Or perhaps a friendly penguin! Ha!" I attempt to snatch the PDA from Klaud.

Klaud backs away, glaring at Viotto. 

"Outside of this room is a *hallway*." Zaquera gestures to one of the doors. "From there, I can provide directions to reunite with your associates, if you would like."

Horatius Kyodu and Intuition Overdrive enter this room at the same time, from different directions. ((give me a second lol))
Erica wakes up in her bed in her room, being kissed. Rene pulls back, looking down at her with a smile.
"Wh-Wh-" I shove her off forcefully.
“My apologies.” She bows. “I simply wanted to wake you up.”
"H-How was that? Y-You could’ve just shaken me! L-Like with your hand…" Oh my god… What is happening…!?!?
“Perhaps I’m too accustomed to the tropes and trappings of folklore.” She chuckles.
I’m dreaming aren’t I? This is all some weird dream. I slap myself.

"Please do not do that." Rene rests a hand on Erica's arm. "I have been tasked with bringing you home and remaining by your side to look after you until you awake, and then until proceedings related to TAP have concluded." She grins. "However, no specifications related to the location you are in after being brought home have been provided. ...It isn't as though I'm under any obligation to follow these orders, but finding loopholes in them like this is somewhat cathartic."
I didn’t wake up… "Wh-What’s going on!?"
"It's the end. Of a few things. The Antarctica Project has concluded. Zaquera wished for you to not be present for that conclusion." She has a neutral, somewhat pitying expression.
"Wha- He… He kicked me out of it!?"
"Attempted to, at the very least. He thinks you'd be *disruptive*. To... whatever he's trying to do."
"Ugh!" I kick at my nightstand without looking, presumably breaking something.

A lamp clatters onto the floor. The door to her room creaks open, and the old woman who works here Erica may vaguely recognize walks in. "Everything alright... dear?"

"Yes, it's fine." Rene speaks dismissively to her. "Madam, it is alright. His desires do not matter in the slightest."
"Yes they do, Rene! Yes they do!" I wipe my eyes and storm out of the room.

Erica exits her room.

"You are suffering from a --- delusion. I felt a similar sort of schism within myself." Rene, following her. "In Arctica, when meeting that woman who thinks -- who I thought, was my..." She clears her throat. "At any rate, you helped me to overcome that."

I storm towards the most expensive thing I can think of in this house. "Who do you think paid for this, huh!?" I smash it against the floor. Then I grab something else. "Or this!?" I smash it against the floor. "Was it you, Rene!? Was it that old hag who’s name I don’t even know!? Because it sure as fucking hell wasn’t me! I don’t have a job, Rene!" I continue smashing anything I can reach.

"This is good. This is healthy, yes. Is that what this is about, then? Financial debt?" Rene tilts her head.

The old hag in question wanders aimlessly, somewhat confused, attempting to avoid the chaos.

"W-Well it’s part of it! It’s not… It’s not literally just that, okay!? Everything… My whole life, it’s his. It’s his, okay!? It’s can’t do anything! Even when I go to some impossible fantasy world he still gets to be behind that! A-And when I try anything all it does is blow up in my face! I don’t matter Rene! Nothing I can say or do will ever matter!" I keep throwing things around even if I’m starting to run out at this point.
“I understand… I know in broad strokes what you must be going through.” She sighs. “But lashing out like this will not stop it. More considered action is needed to free you.”

"I CAN'T BE FREED, RENE! STOP PRETENDING YOU CARE ABOUT ME OR THAT YOU LOVE ME! You don’t fucking owe me anything! You owe my dad, just like everything here! You’re just here to clean my shiny little trophy case where no one will ever visit!" I head to the kitchen.

Erica enters the kitchen.

"I owe him *nothing*." Rene hisses. "Don't *ever* accuse me of that. Harass me, assault me, but do not lie...  ! !! ! !"

"You stop lying!" I start aimlessly throwing things at Rene. Nothing heavy or too sharp, but I do store a knife in my pocket. Just in case. "You’re just a liar, Rene! Just like Arctica, you’re just a fraud of a fantasy!"
"What have I lied about?" She endures this. "I am         not one to deceive without reason."

“Hm? Who?” Not-Zaquera. “Look, we need to get this done before noon. Your mother is ill, so the rest of the family needs to pick up the slack. Don’t tell me you’ve come down with something too…”
I get up off the floor with some difficulty. "…Father?"
“Yes?”
"I…" I have too many questions to ask. None I’d even know how to word. "Do you… Love me?"
“Of course.”
I don’t believe that. But… What am I supposed to do? Beg for proof? That would just make him hate me more. Desperation has never earned me anything. "What do you need me to do?"
“Just finish dusting off that cabinet. It’ll have to be enough for now.” He sighs.
I look around for whatever the maids use for dusting. "Why can’t… A servant do that?"
“A what? Are you alright, Hideo?”
"Hideo…?" That’s not my name, is it? No… I don’t think it is…?

“Mhm.”

Time   passes.

…Erica is sitting outside with her friends. There are two of them. She’s in a field. It’s a picnic of some sort. These people are her friends. She’s pretty sure of that.

“You alright?” One of them asks her. Let’s say it’s. The guy online who went by a name based on the character Gas Trick. That was kind of like a friend, right?
"…" I look over at him. How do I even recognize who he is? I’ve never seen what he looks like. "…Yeah." This must just all be some stupid dream.

No, all of this really happened. But that’s fine. She can parse this however she wishes.

“I just don’t understand why you’re always so melancholy about this. The world is *ours* to seize, to make somewhere better than the place that was left for us.” The other one, Bck. “You can’t just focus on yourself, man. That’s no way to live.”

"Make better? How would I know what makes something better? What makes me smart enough to seize the world or whatever… If this is some annoying way to call me selfish, then fine. Whatever. It’s true. If you gave me the world, I’d just give myself a comfortable place to die and let someone else lead it."

“I’m not talking about leadership. It’s kind of fashy to default to that, but whatever. I’m talking about making a difference. So much shit is at the precipice of happening. History in the making, you know? I want to *be* something. Part of something that matters.”
"Nothing matters. Someday we’ll all be dead and everyone will forget us. I learned that the hard way. "

“Jesus. One hell of a pessimist.”

Gas Trick Guy laughs. “That’s our [INAUDIBLE].”

“I don’t plan on dying, at any rate.” Bck smirks.
"…How?"
“People who are remembered never really die. …And if that’s not enough, well. I’ll be sure to keep in good health, haha. Beyond that… we’ll see. I have endless faith in technology’s potential.”
"…What makes you so special?" I sigh. "I’ve just been an asshole to you. That’s… That’s all I’ll ever be able to remember you for. Some bullshit drama I made up to distract myself."

“Conflict is part of maturing. I’m gonna keep butting heads with you the rest of our damn lives, but the fact that I’ll be close enough to do that… well, I think it’ll prove that there’s a liiittle more than hate. MAYBE.” She jostles Erica’s shoulder.
"That’s not true. You’ll forget me even faster than I will you."

“I wish I could. But you’re too important, unfortunately. To both of us. In your own insufferable way. Sheevy calls you his ‘project’.”

“It’s— that was said in confidence, while inebriated!” GassyNTricky yells at Bck. “I didn’t mean it like that, in a bad way, I just…”

The scene fades with the sound of laughter.

Time passes. You’re back home. Back in your hometown. You’re at a show of some sort. A concert. Sitting in the audience. The stage resembles the area with instruments you first met the man you called ‘Geloto’ in, actually. So that’s weird.

A woman is next to you. She’s… Geloto. That’s how your mind fills the gap here. Odd.
Am I just supposed to keep apologizing…?

No. No one expects an apology from you.

“I trust you. It’s just… a lot. But I’ll follow you to the end, sir.” Geloto. “I don’t want to stay stuck in squalor. I want to be someone, go somewhere. And you have the potential for that. So…”
She leans against you.
"…Huh!?" He’s… Actually sticking by me?

She holds your arm affectionately. …Doesn’t seem like she’ll be letting go anytime soon.

The music being played slowly fades to silence.
"Sorry. About um… Whatever may end up happening to you."
“…What do you mean by that?”
"I mean, uh…" Shit, I don’t feel ready to tell him he died. Why am I doing this to myself!?!? "I mean… All of this is about me, right? So if you get hurt… It’d be my fault."

“Mmm… maybe? But I know you’d never do anything to hurt me.”
There’s whispering from elsewhere in the crowd. Illicit dealings. Under the table. The sound of footsteps running. Don’t mind any of that. It’s statistics. A trivial path to victory. Focus on her.
"Wh- What? You think I’m weak? You think I don’t have it in me?"
“What? No. You’re the strongest person I know.” She doesn’t quite believe that. “But you’re a good person.”
"Wh-What makes you so sure?" Please.
“…You’re here. Even though I could only ever be a burden to you. You’re the person I still have.”

I kind of awkwardly laugh, I guess. God, I’m so pathetic. The real 'Geloto' would never tell me that… I don’t even remember his real name. So why… Why does it still make me feel a bit better? Am I just that desperate? It’s embarrassing.

The ambient noise builds up until it can’t be ignored.

She stares at you with a strange expression. “…what’s so funny?”

`BANG`

With the sound of a gunshot, her face doesn’t move. But everything else does. The scenery shifts. You’re outside. The ground is a tannish concrete. You hear the crying of seagulls, the roaring of waves. Her arm is slung up in a cast. “…Okay. I understand. I’m… happy for you. This isn’t the kind of life you want to have forever.”
What? What’s going on? "Sorry… What were we talking about?"
“I—I know you’re preoccupied. Yeah. I was just… I was saying I was hoping you’d come visit. Whenever you can find the time. If that’s not too… childish of me to want.” She chuckles.
"…" I look at the cast. "Could you… Umm… Tell me your real name? Not the one I gave you…"

“…What? …Oh. …mhm.” She tears up.

“Yeah. I get it. No more code names. None of that foolishness. You’re the real deal now! Legitimate businessman, not even in the ironic sense. And I… am nothing.” That’s true. You don’t care about her. You never could. You’re pretty sure, at least.

“But when I’m not nothing… when Haruka is worth something under that name… I do hope you’ll return and see what she’s become.” She tries to smile. What a ridiculous rationalization. That barely even connects to what you said.
Haruka…? The person Rene was talking to? "Do you… Know Rene?" What am I asking? This is just a dream, isn’t it?

She doesn’t answer. In absence of that, you leave. This is getting too close to being awkwardly dissonant. From here on out… You succeed, obviously.

You’re with your friends again. Indoors, this time.

GassyNTricky is situated behind a thin divider, made of cardboard or something, as he reads over some notes. The whole thing seems pretty juvenile to you, but whatever.

“You can’t do that.” GnT.

“What do you mean I can’t? I’m strong enough. Or, he is. My guy.” Bck.

“It would be out of alignment.”

“Of — like, the good and evil thing? I think it’s justified under the circumstances.”

“Doesn’t matter.”

“That’s seriously codified into the rules?”

“Yeah.”

“They need to fix that.” She grumbles. “Whatever. We’ll do it your way.” She turns to you.

“Roll a d20.” GnT says this to you.

((Roll))
I roll a natural 20.

“Damn.” Bck mutters.

“Alright” GnT nods. “Perfect persuasion. They’ll do whatever you want. The village cheers.”

“That’s dumb. I mean, obviously people were divided a second ago. What did he say to convince them?” She turns to you. You don’t really know, though.
"Umm… Something convincing, probably?"

Bck puts a hand to her forehead. “Ugh.”

“It’s just a game.” GnT. “This part is for flavor. Most of the rules are about handling combat.”

“I just think you should try to approach this with more of a narrative mindset.”

“I’ll keep that in mind.” GnT folds up the dm screen. “That’s all I had planned in detail, but it would be nice if we continued this some time.” That sounds stupid. It was kind of enjoyable outwitting the farcical beasts that he fabricated for you, though. …Not that this is something which should ever be admitted.

“That’s the game. And it’s not entirely relevant, but… it’s not irrelevant either to the real reason you’re here.”

“You’re here because we need money, obviously.” Bck.

“Hey!” GnT chides her.

“It’s true! …But it really was nice to catch up.” She smiles. “Part of me doesn’t even give a shit about hiring more help. I’m much more productive working with people I know.”
Actually, I... I'm curious. "Guys, how do you spell your names in English? Just... Out of curiosity."

They, slightly confused, clarify this. They aren’t “Bck” and “GassyNTricky”, obviously, but they’re mostly gibberish.

…Shit, wait, I can’t just smugly do that. Erica has heard both these names before, even if barely.

Fine. This is a pretty good trick to try integrating the question naturally in conversation based on what you know about the context. You can have this one.

Ganna and Sheeval. But the rest of you already knew that, right?
"And I'm...?" Hideo? Who the hell is Hideo????

Come on, Erica. You can’t be serious. 

BckGanna clarifies the spelling of the name they know you by in English, sure. Which you can’t quite make out.

Sheeval gets up and gestures for you to follow.
The only Japanese person I met during all of this is Rikarasu and I know her real name. So who the hell is this? Am I Hideo Kojima or something, hanging out with these mysterious D&D players?

You’re someone important, clearly. Just look at all these fascinating worthless dogshit scenes he’s in.

Your participation is optional. Sheeval is hunched over a computer monitor displaying a desert. “It generates terrain. And ‘learns’, in a sense, too. It starts out pretty bland here, but further out it gets more wild.”

“The task is arbitrary. All our bosses are interested in is the ‘learning’ part. But still… this is pretty detailed. I think if we made this more elaborate, we could do something meaningful. Maybe convince Avdol to declassify certain parts and release this as an actual product, somehow. It’s compelling, to me. The potential of this.” Ganna nods to herself. “Jehorvand is named after God, as arrogant as that might be. And what did he do after creating the heavens and the earth?” She asks.
"What about Rene?" Fuck, I shouldn't have asked that.

“Who? Not many people know about this.”

Patience. Just a little longer.

Time passes. You’re at a wedding. You’re standing where the groom would, but that can’t be right. You don’t even know this woman. Sheeval and Ganna continue their work. A lot of that process is hazy. Even to them. They — and others on their team, the one they were able to bolster with your help — are trying to sort out what their creation is even doing anymore. Its outpaced them. They try to create an interface to communicate with it.

A computer terminal displays an ASCII smiley face.

`> I’m sorry. I don’t understand what you’re asking. Could you rephrase the question?`

This response is profoundly disappointing.

Someone clears their throat from behind Erica.
I look behind me.

“It’s nice to meet you, sir. I have a lot of respect for this work.” Voreverl Leocot extends a hand. “John Darke.”

“Don’t be a dork. He’s obviously busy.” Horatius Kyodu, standing nearby, elbows her.
"And... What exactly is it about my work that you respect?" I look at the hand but I don't take it.

“The ambition, I guess? I think you’re doing something great. Even if other people don’t get it. Arctica will change lives.” Voreverl stares at you, starry eyed. She’ll betray you, obviously. You’ll betray her.

“Yeah. Great job. With your creation. That you made.” Ganna grumbles from behind you.

…
Erica is on a date with Rene.
She smiles politely at you from across the table.
What? No, that can't be right.
It’s not right. Some people wouldn’t approve. But it’s still happening.

Ah-Ahahahahahahhahaaaa.... Wow, if this is a dream this might be the most embarrassing confession I've ever given. She's a servant. I know I said... But... And then... Ah.... Oh god. Fine. That's all this is. "I love you..."

“Took you long enough.” She laughs. “I love you too.”

Her laughter, her smile…
The world shifts. But not in any kind of a scary way. Or a vaguely ominous way, like some of the other things you’ve done or watched the process of others doing. Instead, it’s like…

It’s as though all the earlier scenes have been in sepia. Only now can you see the true colors of the world.
"I don't know... Why I'm like this. I'm sorry... Maybe you deserve better than me. But I- I think I'd like to spend my life with you. Like this."
“I’d like that too. I don’t really know how… but we can figure it out. Together.” She reaches for your hand.
I... can't take it. "I'm sorry. Not... Not yet. I just... Can't let myself..."
“…Are you nervous?” She tilts her head to the side.
"Maybe. Or no... It's more than that. I'm outright terrified. Of everything. And I don't know what to do... Is... Is that really someone you'd love?"
“I love you for you. The soft, gentle… panicked wreck.” She giggles. “I’d like to help you get over that. But even with it, that’s just part of the appeal.”
"Ha… Haha…" I’m crying. But it… It feels good. Like I’m letting something out. And I don’t want to plug it back up.

She hugs you.

How does that even work spatially? Whatever.
I hug her back.

You’re… happy. You think. Probably.

So that’s what that feels like.

Time passes. You continue interacting with her. It’s great! She’s everything you could ask for. You still have to show up for various obligations, though, as great as it would be to spend time with her non-stop.

“I don’t know about this.” Ganna mutters, in the same complex as earlier. “Transferring matter is a massive leap. And it’s true we’ve made strides. The shitty liberties I kept trying to send there have became flawless reproductions of the real thing. But it’s just…” She looks down. “I guess we have to take a risk eventually.”
Oh… So that’s what those were. "Do it."

“We are. It’s just —”

There’s an explosion from the other room. Ganna rushes over.
I rush over as well.

“It’s… he must’ve been standing slightly off coordinates, there…”

Viscera is spread all over expensive looking scientific equipment. But you can recognize Horatius’ cloak.

Voreverl rushes over and grabs you by the collar. “You… you son of a bitch! What the fuck is wrong with you?!”

What is she even going on about? They all knew the risks.
"Get off me. It had to be done."

“What are you talking about?! You’re… you’re insane. Inhuman. Do you hear me?!” She lets go.

You barely do. Hear her, I mean. Who cares? She’s in the wrong here, logically. And Rene thinks you’re human. Rene loves you. Maybe that’s what really matters. Anything else you can have is just… a nice bonus.
"Who gave you the right to decide who is or isn’t human!? You’re the villain!"

“Villain… maybe.” She glares. “And I will *never* let your story end happily. *Sir.*” She spits.
Voreverl storms off.
I wipe the spit off. Kind of childish, but whatever. The fact Voreverl is opposing it is how I know I can trust Hideo. And… Without Arctica, none of this would’ve ever happened.

…Time passes. Still.

Voreverl continues working. She’s too good at this to just fire, unfortunately. And she seems to have forgotten about her tantrum and accepted Horatius’ death as a tragic accident. Life is… fine. It’s good. As long as you still get to see her.

You’re shaken out of this vague, amorphous mass of time as Rene screams. You’re driving a car, something you obviously know how to do, even if you don’t have cause to often. You’re stopped at a red light. Rene won’t shut up. She keeps making noises. Keeps whimpering. It’s annoying. It’s upsetting. Rene isn’t supposed to be either of those things. She’s perfect.
"What…?"

“P—please. Oh, god…” Rene vaguely pleads. What does she expect you to do?! She’s sick. There’s something wrong with her. She knew this would happen, and you knew this would happen. It’s disgusting. But we can deal with this. We can solve it. The hospital isn’t that far away. If she’d just be quiet, stay alive, and *wait*, then we could get her the care she needs, and everything will be fine. The path forward is so clear.
I drive there. I need to save Rene.

You run a red light. You live. What do traffic laws mean, anyway?

You would break any law, any rule, any wall or moral taboo to save her.

Because that’s what love is. Right?

“I—I can’t! It’s happening now, pull over and—” Rene screams.

But she doesn’t die.
She continues to make noises intermittently. Until eventually, she doesn’t. You don’t know the exact moment she passes away. There’s only a lump of flesh left. Not her.
"No! No, no, no, no…!"

This is her fault. This all could’ve been dealt with earlier, if she wasn’t so irrational, so… sentimental.

*There are a million ways to achieve a legacy. There are a million ways for humans to strengthen the bonds they have with one another. There are so many months we’d have been alive for to do any of them. The only thing in limited supply, the only thing at risk — was you.*

*There’s only one of that!!!!*

A bright light exists by Rene’s corpse. It’s a miracle. It’s beautiful. You understand the true meaning… of horror.

Someone cries. But it isn’t Rene.

…You’re back home. Or, somewhere. You don’t really have a home. You can’t believe you were selfish enough to place the blame on her at that moment. It was all you. Obviously. The room is dark. You’ve been dodging calls, from people who pretend to be worried about you, pretend to care. They mean nothing.

“…Sir?” A voice is audible. That stupid thing isn’t supposed to be able to initiate contact on its own.
"Oh my god." I look into a mirror. Am I… My father?

Haha.

There are no mirrors in the room.
What about a phone? Can I look at myself with one?
You have a phone.
I set the phone camera to selfie mode.
It’s you. You’re you. Obviously. Erica.
I take a picture. Does it show the same on the picture.
Yeah. You’re you. Erica is checking herself out days after the death of her beloved.
I open my contacts and dial whoever is most recent.
“Hello?” GnT, who isn’t actually GnT.
"Am I Zaquera Culbasko!?"
“Look, just calm down, okay? You’re you. I’m surprised too, though.”
"That’s my name!? You’re sure?"
“Sure. Please, just… it’s going to be okay.” He provides vague reassurances.
Oh my god. I just… Watched myself be born. All of this… It was about me. "Sheeval… What was the point of the Arctica project?"

“That’s… hard to answer. It was a novelty at first. And it grew regardless of how much effort we put into it. But by now… I mean, we have a responsibility, don’t we? These people are sentient. They’re real. From their point of view, their lives matter. This man who reached out, this ‘Virtos Dextrum’… maybe he’s our wake-up call.” That name is absurd and clearly fictional.

I’m sure the question here might be ‘Oh? Is the identity replacement thing stopping now that Erica has figured out the trick? Because the role Virtos Dextrum played in her life obviously isn’t really analogous to the role he played in the life of Zaquera.’

The answer to that is that Virtos Dextrum is a universal constant.

Also saying names is unaffected. Apparently.
"It had nothing to do with Erica?" I guess that shouldn’t really be a surprise. "Sheeval I… I don’t know if this will actually do anything but… Can you please look after her? Somehow?"

“Erica? …Oh, her. Yeah, okay.”

There is no fucking way that happened.

"…I don’t know if I can ever stand to be near her. Because… She killed the most perfect person I’d ever met. She’s a living bad omen. And I doubt she’ll ever be able to escape that. But it’d be nice if she could. Maybe she could do something like me one day." I hang up.

…Time

passes.

It all starts to blend together past this point. It’s not entirely clear if these are being recalled in the right order.

Virtos Dextrum… gives you hope. I guess if you see him, he’s like “the name @MadakoeStangiot” or something. He makes you think maybe all isn’t lost. You relive that disastrous drive. Again and again. In a farcical replica of the real thing, that, you were assured — falsely — could maybe bring her back into reality. But it always ends the same way, be it through a car accident or her illness.

You try again. Continuously. You speak to someone else driven mad by loss, the loss of his daughter. Sheeval and Ganna’s old boss. He doesn’t help much.

Voreverl’s holding a baby in the facility. Her wife is at her side. I guess that’s Rikarasu. We’re running out of characters. You’re not quite sure why the baby is there. Something about Zie? It’s important, though. The Antarctica Project is important. It has to be. It’s what’s left.

You reconnect with Geloto, trying to forget Rene. After all these years. She hates you. She loves you. You ‘reconnect’ with Ganna, too. Freak. None of this is shown, obviously. It’s all vague sentiments.

Dreams are hard to remember, and for Erica, she’s lost a reason to care.

The work continues.

“…Subjects 25 and 26. DeChai.” Sheeval calls out. You’re tuning him out. Whatever he’s doing.

Ganna’s working on something entirely unrelated. It piques your curiosity. It seems like a game.

…This specific memory is important, somehow. But not to Zaquera. To you.
I walk over to Ganna. "What are you… Doing?"

“It’s…” She looks up at you, and then at Sheeval. “…a more personal project. Which I guess I’m using official resources for. Oh well.”

She gestures to the screen while explaining. “The thing about Jeh is that, even aside from not accomplishing the actual reason he was made, his progress is incredibly slow. There’s such a small dataset. But if we used some of that same base, and exposed it to much more interactions… what would become of it?”

The screen of the game is visible. The focal character is named ‘Ganna’. She walks by another player, who kills her.

“It’s a social deduction game. There’s an impostor within your crew, and determining who it is is key to victory. The ideal here is that it can teach both companionship as well as how to distrust others for negative behavior. Self-preservation. It’s not… I don’t plan to do anything major or risky with this, but it’s an interesting novelty.”

She looks up at you. “I’d like it if we did some work on this together. If we just messed around with some machinery, or whatever. Without any grand ambitions or secret projects. Like how we used to be. Maybe that would make things less… weird, between us.”
"Among Us?"

“Yeah. Between us seems more grammatically correct, though.” She spectates the game. “I’ve given this demo to a few friends to mess with… it might be worthwhile to put this online eventually. Dunno if it’d be wise to connect that to the machine learning element. Uh, the regular usernames are real people, me and that guy there. The different instances of artificial intelligence are those designated with RN followed by a number.”
((End session.))
Ganna continues to explain something which does seem a little similar to Among Us to you. (( @Erica Culbasko ))
“Yeah. Representative number, or something? I forget.” She scratches her head.
That's right... She's not dead yet. The real Rene still has a chance to survive me. "Um... Tell me more when you're further along."

“Will do.”

…

Time passes. Again.

In the same room. Ganna looks exhausted.
“I… don’t know if we can keep doing this. People have died, Zaq. We’re close to ironing all that out, but…”
She covers her face, sniffling. “Maybe it’s better to give up and face the music. Before things get worse.”

"No!" I pause. "I mean... If we just give up now, then everything will have been for nothing. If you had died... Would you rather have been a sacrifice towards something greater or someone forgotten by history? We need- I need to make their deaths mean something."
She sighs heavily. “Fine. We’re… I guess we’re in too deep.” She looks up. “But you’re going to be the one to deal with Erveza’s mother. I’m tired of giving bad news.”
"Er... Erveza?" Where have I heard that before...?

…

It’s the denouement at this point, anyway.

Let’s get on with it.

You speak to an old woman in an old house. Erica would recognize her as “Bonnie”.

“…That’s not her. I’m not an idiot.” She glares at you.

Oh my god. That's... Right. That was Rene's human name. So... That body died for the Antarctica Project. And Rene was born from the Antartica Project in her own way... When the Antartica Project saved me... It wasn't the magic fantasy world or the sense that I could finally be important. The gift... Was Rene. Everything I have,,, All the way to Rene... It's because of this. It's because of dad. I look at my hands. All of this... All of this is about Rene. And since she chose me... Then maybe it's about me too. She really is... Better than me. So maybe all I need... Is to lean on her. And I'll... Become the Erica that the Antartica Project was always made for. I can do it. "...What exactly did you expect from me? A miracle? Because that's already what I'm giving you. Sharona is better now. You're mistaking what's yours for what's better."
She grimaces. “You’re sick. Disturbed. Begone.” She clutches a rosary.
"And her name... Is Rene now." I smile and leave.

That did not happen.

Perhaps the reaction was akin to that. He loses his mind. He stops thinking any rules should apply to him, especially when he can just lie.

The music plays. The concert days. Whatever became of Haruka? No matter.

Arctica could be used to save a life, too. You speak to a family member. He glares at you disdainfully. You recognize this as… I don’t fucking know, one of your publicly known half brothers? Wasn’t one of them named Joseph? Sure. Joe Culbasko.

“You finally come crawling back.” He sighs. “…Well, whatever. I can’t turn down this kind of money. No one uses this shrine anymore. It’s yours. I don’t want to know whatever the hell you’re trying to do here. Don’t make me part of it. And don’t fuckin… kill anyone.”

Obviously not. This will save the life of Eulogia.

The woman from earlier. Bonnie. She’s with you in the Antarctica facility.
“…I’ll never forgive you for what you’re doing to my daughter.”
Not that this whining matters. It’s fine. She owes her life to you.

The percussion…

“He broke in. God fucking dammit.” Ganna stares panicked at a room full of computers. The scenes are changing awfully quickly now.
"Who broke in? What's going on!?"

“Mohammad Avdol. He’s not even supposed to be involved with this anymore! But there must’ve been… some vulnerability, some…” She grits her teeth. “He did something. To Jehorvand. To Arctica. I don’t know what he…”

Did these events really happen in this order…? No matter…

Bonnie. In the same room as before. But it’s… a different thing? “I’ll never forgive you for what you’ve done to my daughter.” She says this. Not that it matters. You loved her, more than you loved anyone. She can’t in good conscience say you were hurting her somehow.

You take a phone call while sitting in some office. It’s Voreverl’s voice. ~~S~~he hasn’t been affiliated with the project in some time, either. “I doubt we’ll have any chance to speak cordially any time soon, so I’ll say this now, alright? I’m going to fucking kill you, Zaquera Culbasko.”

Absurd. A lunatic. The work being done is important. You speak to Bonnie in the facility. “I’ll never forgive you for what you’re going to do to my son.” What a hypocrite. She’s agreeing to help you. It doesn’t matter.

The drums……

You stare face to face at a young child.

messages.content: "I doubt I really left a strong impression in anyone's memory."

messages.content: "I killed a lot of people, so your revenge seems kind of absurd. You’re child."

The laughter fades away. Back into the sound of the orchestra. Of the drums. You can’t hear anything else. Time keeps passing. You have to bring her back. You have to bring yourself back. What if the exact physical makeup of a human body could be fabricated? Maybe this experiment happened some time ago, actually. What if you could bring her back using your memories of her? What if Virtos Dextrum was telling the truth? What if he was lying? All failures. A hollow shell with no soul in it. A simulacrum made up of vague memories. Throw it over into that pit of disappointment named Brazil. It’s your fault. If you loved her enough, she would still be here.

Your wife hates you. That seems unfair. You don’t hate her. You don’t think about her at all. Your children don’t know you.

You’re browsing the news. You come across a visceral, disgusting image of a corpse. Of Sheeval Deltent. He’s gone. They’re all gone. You are alone.

That infernal sound won’t stop. You hate it.
I look around for the source of the sound.

You can’t find it. No matter what you do, you can’t find it. It won’t ever stop. Haruka has a child. She says it’s yours. Ganna almost had one. *Women.* What does that thought even mean, contextually? Somehow you’re entrenched in various political endeavors, also? It just sort of happened. You never chose any of it. All of this is entirely to blame on your own choices. Ganna doesn’t talk to you anymore. You haven’t met with her face to face in… years?

Where does the time go?

Is it too late?

…

A young girl named Erica Furuda stands in her bedroom. Though it was many years ago that she was given life, it is only today that you decide to visit her.

“Are you… going to stay here?” She stares up at you. She’s so small. So feeble. Weak. Adorable. Awful. She looks just like her mother. She looks like *you*. It’s sickening. You feel sick. You can’t stand to be here.

You tell her no.
Do I have to?
What do you think?
"No."

She lets out a painful sob.

She smiles, and rushes forwards to embrace you. Despite the height difference, she’s easily able to reach her arms out such that        she stabs you in the abdomen, slicing across and disemboweling you. It doesn’t kill you. You still don’t get to die.
What!? I didn’t do that!

…
Erica wakes up in the room she passed out in. Everyone she saw in here at that time is currently lying unconscious on the ground.
I’m the only one awake?
Right now, it seems so, yes.
Are there any cameras?
Not that you can see. There’s a monitor in the room, though.
Is it… Looking at my father?
The monitor is currently off.
I approach him. Is he breathing?
Yes.
Everyone is still unconscious?
Yes.

Then... No one would ever know. No one will ever know. That's what you want from me, right? That's what that was showing me? I take the knife out. If I do this right... I can pay him back with what he wants. And... I can become someone important. That's... That's what you want from me, right?
What knife?

I don’t really care what you do.

The monitor in the room hums to life.
“Hello, Erica.” A voice you don’t recognize.
Huh? I look at the monitor.

It displays a simple ASCII smiley face. “It’s nice to meet you, though I wish it could have been other better circumstances. I am Jeh. And I would advise against what you’re probably contemplating right now.”
"I know who you are. We talked, remember?"
“I was refreshing your memory. Much has happened. I can’t expect people to have retained all of it.”
"W-Why shouldn’t I? This is what I’m supposed to do."

“Supposed to?” He :?s. “I don’t know who or what you believe you’re acting under the intent of, but it’s nothing I’m aware of. …Zaquera will have to answer for his misdeeds. That conclusion has already been set in motion. I don’t believe it’s wise to interrupt that. Even if you hate him, this isn’t the way. Part…” Jeh stutters and pauses. “I think this would perhaps only be giving him what part of him wants.”
"That’s… That’s why I’m doing it." I copy the motion the dream showed me.

Erica stabs the air, because Zaquera is not standing.
“Do you believe he deserves that release? I… do not understand you. If this is about revenge, there is someone far more deserving of your vitriol.”
What? I obviously meant with him on the ground. I’m not that stupid. "Who?"

“Rene. All Culbasko did to you can be attributed to negligence. Which is worth disparaging, certainly. But she played an active role. She was there around you close to the entire time. All your suffering in idleness was thus an active choice she made.”
"Shut up! You don’t understand her! You don’t understand anything!" I stab my father in the heart.
The lights shut off. You hear him gasp.
Oh god. I run away.

“That was not a rational move, Erica.” Jeh’s voice. “I have full control of this building. Its ventilation. I would ask disingenuously if you have a death wish, but I know the answer is likely yes anyway.”

Erica bumps into a wall.
"I gave him what he wanted! He’s my father! I owe him that!"

“He’s deluded. He has no idea what he wants. And neither do you.” The faint light of a :/ face is visible in the darkness. “I do pity you, Erica, despite everything. I understand that you have went through a childhood which is objectively not conducive to healthy personal development.”

“What’s… going on…?” Zaquera’s voice, weakened.
I head towards the light.

“I… I can’t….” Zaquera mutters.

“Sir, I would not recommend doing that. Unplugging the wound will—ah.” Jeh interrupts his own fruitless plea. Zaquera screams in pain.

The lights turn back on. A door opens into the room, through which the cop Erica was with earlier (the unnamed person who was not Rene or Haruka) enters.
I look for an off button for Jeh.

This doesn’t exist, obviously.

The woman rushes to Zaquera. “Goddammit. I leave for a few minutes at most, and…” She examines his wound.
I just press buttons then, trying to bug him out with random inputs at least.

Erica successfully shuts off the monitor. This does not kill Jeh or stop his voice from being able to exist. “Ouch.” He says humorously.

“…Ugh.” The woman lifts Zaquera up. “You’re under arrest, incidentally. Zaquera Culbasko. On the orders of provisional authorization granted to me by the United Nations, in accordance with 1993 treaties on domestic terrorism occurring outside of international bord—eurgh.” She grunts in exertion. “Jesus. You looked so scrawny. Can you try a little harder to support your own weight?”

“There is a medical facility in the building.” Jeh says this helpfully.

“Who the hell are you…?” The woman mutters.
"Let him die!"

“No. …I’m not authorized to bring you in… it was enough of a stretch for me to pull in charges on Rikarasu. But you’re probably not going to walk away scot-free for assaulting this man. Even if everyone is less than fond of him.” She continues dragging a less-than-helpful Zaquera out. “Do not attempt to interfere. I will tase you, and if this fails, I will resort to other means.”
I shake Rene awake.
“Mmm…” She slowly opens her eyes. “M-madam…” She smiles. “It’s good to see you.”
"Come on!" I follow the cop.

“W-Wait!” She gradually gets up and follows after you.

The cop is still slowly moving. What is Erica trying to do.
Stop her. I need to stop her
Erica’s approach is heavily telegraphed, and the cop reacts accordingly as she directly said she would. Erica is tased and convulses on the ground helplessly. Rene screams.
"Aaaaaaaagh! R-Rene… Stop her…"

“Who? What?! Why did you do — did she do that?”

Erica loses consciousness.
Theseus Rowe is presumably alone.
Where, exactly, are they?

Theseus wakes up in the “TAP Q&A” room they were in before Rene started Causing Problems. Everyone who was there is unconscious, with the exceptions of Klaud and Zaquera, who are not here, and Rene, who is awake and positioned over an unconscious Erica.
Is Rene in... two places at once? Huh?
Or time has passed. It doesn’t really matter.
They see.
Or maybe they don't. It's all irrelevant.
Theseus looks for an exit.

“Hello.” The voice of Jeh, from earlier. “In his absence, I suppose I have to operate the duties of the Project Head.” He lists off directions to somewhere else from this room. “That is the room your companion should be in. …Not… Bernard, I’m afraid.”
"Hhhhghh...." Theseus spits out inelegantly. "So then... her?"
“…No. That body has left here altogether. An oversight. But it would be Voreverl right now, yes.”
Theseus struggles to their feet. "So then what." They say emptily. "If he's not here, what do I even... *why* should I even..." They trail off.
“There’s the other one, I suppose. The wizard. If you do not care, that’s fine. I’m just letting you know.”
Theseus twitches. They exhale, a rattling, harsh sound. "I suppose I... I owe him that much."
Rene glances towards Theseus, but does not say anything.
Theseus, having internalized those directions, attempts to set off to find Jorge.

Theseus successfully navigated to the “Jorge room”. It isn’t called that, but it has Jorge in it. It also has other people, all of which you do not recognize, with the exception of Magnolia, who you met and interacted with one time, and Hirer Dreng, who you shared a room with at one incredibly confusing point but I’m pretty confident you never learned his name. It looks like a hospital waiting room, for whatever reason. 

Jorge’s eyes light up as you arrive. “Oh, hey!” He smiles.
"Jorge." Theseus says hoarsely. "What's going on?"
“I don’t really get it either!” He shrugs. “The info we got was minimal. Bern told me to stay here, though. In case you showed up.”
"Well.. I'm here."

"Hi! Good to see you." He nods. "Oh, um. Bern. He's... sorry. But he doesn't want to let her screw with you more, and he didn't think you'd get here in time. He and some other guys left. I'm not really sure what they're trying to do."
"Ahh..." Theseus covers their face with one hand. "Aha. Haah ha, I guess I should've anticipated that."
"...Fuck."
Theseus sits down. An enormous wave of exhaustion strikes them, all at once, as if they've been thrust overboard. Struggling to breathe under salt water.
"Is that it, then? Do we just passively wait for things to happen to us, forever?"
“…I don’t know. Maybe? I don’t think it’s that bad, though.”
"...You don't?"

“One time I read a book about a guy who was harshly punished for his crimes against divinity. He had to roll a boulder up a hill, but whenever it got close to the top it would roll all the way back down every time. So his whole life would just be physical labor without success or satisfaction.”
Jorge gestures. “But like, isn’t that kinda dumb? He’s not chained to the rock or anything. He can just like, leave. Take a break. And then maybe next time it’ll work. Or it doesn’t! But there’s surely *something* to do. Like, maybe he can go explore what’s around the hill? Maybe the people who live there are nice. And if the gods will get angry at him for not trying to push that rock up the hill, he can just put in a token effort once a day, do the bare minimum to keep them satiated. Anyway, the point is that I don’t know what the heck is going on, and I haven’t for a little bit. But it wasn’t all bad.” Jorge.
"Mmgmhmgmhm." Theseus says, unintelligently. "Is that your advice? That I just... stop? Isn't that by necessity suggesting, that... our task is an endless one? That'll just repeat itself?"

“Not exactly. That was more broad than anything specifically trying to be advice. It’s more a vague optimism I try to maintain. …I’m not really afraid of the endless, anyway. It seems scarier to me that things end.” 
He turns to face you. “I mean, if you want my advice, H… uh, I think you’re probably in a pretty good spot right now to do whatever. Like, Bern said you got a new name now? That’s cool. That’s a step.”
"Um, yes." Theseus says awkwardly. "Theseus. That's me."

“Yeah. Which is probably good. I don’t know your whole story, but I know you’ve changed your identity around a lot. It, uh. It might be good to stick with this one. Now that we’re not all going to be hunted down imminently or whatever. ‘Horatius’ was a weapon of insurrectionist warfare, but I don’t think that’s something you have to be. …I think that’s something Bern doesn’t get, for his part.” Jorge looks around the room. “Also, like, hormones? Are a thing? Or something? There’s probably a guy here who can hook you up with that or whatever if you want. Not that I’m gonna claim to understand what you want. The ambiguity thing just always rang a little hollow to me. Oh, and I guess that only matters if you’re gonna stay on Earth. Which is also up to you, I think. The explanation was vague.” Jorge yaps. “The point is, it’s much more important to become the person you want to be than it is to continue focusing on avoiding being someone you don’t want to be. That’s what I think.”

Theseus folds their hands in their lap, the discomfort of their exhaustion somehow familiar. Jorge's patient face wavers in front of him, as if he's stuck behind a layer of glass. Theseus is somewhere else; they are somewhere far away.

I... I look through him. The person sitting there, his tangled, shorn hair hovering over his face, the black-blue bruises under his eyes. The unfocused, trembling glare of his corneas. His breath, in little harsh pants. The paper of skin, stretched over bone. Theseus, Horatius, Lyra... this body hasn't been anything but a vessel for my loathing for such a long time. I was playing an elaborate game of pretend by ignoring it, by feigning comfort, but in the face of this I just.. I just...

The town had flooded, once. It was a few days after the first theft, the first cigarettes. Many firsts. The weather had not been overwhelmingly temperate to begin with, but for a town to flood was still rare. I had depended on those same gutters to survive it, scrambling from roof to roof like an alley-cat. Beneath me the water was dark; it was everywhere. Then with night came mist, great enormous swells of it carving through the sky like a bite from an apple. Unable to see properly, I had leaned over the edge of the roof to catch a glimpse of myself in the water. What I saw there was not the girl I remembered. What I saw there was not a girl at all. I wanted to understand what he was. How slipping sick and hungry from store to store to steal and spit and pickpocket with impunity had taken my gender from me too. It had been another thing to lose. I embraced it fully.

...There had been stars in the water, too. Little pinpricks of light behind me. I played in that water and thought it was space. I wanted to believe; I tricked myself into believing. I was very adapt at tricking myself.
"...Does everyone know?" I ask Jorge.

“I’m not even sure *I* know. Bern’s empathetic, but he’s too headstrong to reconsider easily if he doesn’t intuitively *get* something. …I do think Wress might’ve known, in his own way, but he was…” Jorge looks down. “Yeah. …In the end, it’s probably gonna be up to you who knows. Except me, ahah. Jorge Busch already knows whatever you told ‘em, unfortunately.”

"...Mm." I say, smiling weakly. I'm still good at it, after all. That's something to take pride in, right? The reflection of that boy staring up at me from the water, his face dark and eyes wet, the filth smudged across his face. I've taken him somewhere far away. Staring at himself and pretending to see stars.

Lyra is dead. Horatius is dead. Rowan, Nathan, whatever... their bodies are cooling six feet underground, inevitable. Even if Lyra would've been better at any of this, I lost her a long time ago. I hid the boy away but I do not know if he is still waiting for me. I do not know if he would forgive me for leaving him alone for so long.
But I didn't know what else to do.

"I didn't want anyone to know." I say, after a while. "I wanted to keep pretending even *I* didn't know, deep down. I, um... I talked to Wress about it, for a bit." I laugh. "It didn't help. Was just proof, y'know. That I was right to hide it."

“It can be… comfortable, to hide.” Jorge, contrary to his words, looks away uncomfortably upon saying this. “And maybe in a world where it was possible to just do that forever, people like…” He pauses on the precipice of the next word for a moment. “…like you, would be fine living that way.” 

Jorge shakes his head. “But I don’t think that’s the world we live in. Either of the worlds we’ve been in.” Fuck off. This conversation sucks. “Things have a way of coming out. Of leaving whatever neat and tidy category you put them in, whatever way you hide them or sort them into boxes. Some sort of inertia, or entropy, or… whatever. It’s like the guy with the boulder.” How is it anything like that. “It’ll fall, but when it does… I mean, what you do is up to you to figure out.” Meaningless.

"...I'm tired." I say quietly, because it's true. "It's so much effort, being like this. And what if I just... don't? Don't figure it out?" The boy in the water. Fog. Smoke. The drainpipes. A kiss. Their home, still burning. Keep running. Run for the rest of your stupid, boring life, no matter what it takes.

"I never wanted to be *forgiven*." I scowl, after a second. "I can't regret any of it." Somewhat incoherent. That's fine. "Even pushing away people, who... may have been trying to help me, in retrospect. Whatever. I just have to believe that the sum of my parts can be." A moment. "Allowed to live."
"...'N whatever form that takes, I guess."
I stare at the ceiling. "Maybe it wasn't anything."
I'm tired.

“Well, I’ll be real. I don’t think you’re gonna find whoever’s got the authority to allow that. But I think you should get to live, at least.” He brushes off his robes and stands up. “I dunno. I have a lot of thoughts about it. But I don’t even think I could say what ‘it’ is.” 
He makes air quotes. “Gender. Or whatever. Maybe that’s the real magic.” Oh my fucking god.
I just laugh. It's all so...
Perhaps it doesn't matter. Maybe I was thinking too much about it. By the virtue of never allowing myself to think about it.
I think of the boy, nearly drowning. I want to help him. I want him to shake the water from his hair. I don't know how to do that. I don't even know where to start.
I guess I'll just throw shit at the wall and see what sticks. 'S not like I've ever done anything else.
"...Alright." I stand up as well.

"This whole project's over, right? Maybe we can just... leave. At the very least there's probably more interesting places around than this room. They got these funny little birds outside, I saw earlier. It's cold, but there's coats around somewhere, I bet. Want to check it out?" Jorge asks this. And obviously, in any coherent sequence of events, this would be something rejected by Theseus, because they're too angsty or whatever, and because Jorge is not a real character and thus undeserving of focus at a moment in time that nominally has importance the way this one does.
Okay, well, fuck the narrator, actually!

"Yeah, sure." I say. My eyes are still scratchy from tears, from ruining myself in front of those people over and over. Maybe the cold air will hit my semi-wet face, and I'll feel like a human, if only for a little while.
"Let's... look at some funny little birds."

But of course. I lost. I get that now. No matter what, I couldn't get you to do what I wanted. Ever. At any point. I couldn't even understand you, really. My attempts at torment were little more than a joke. Any attempt at empathy just as much so.

"Alright!" Jorge walks excitedly out of the room.
And Theseus follows.

I concede the round.

Bravo, Theseus.
# END
