Voreverl doesn't really pay attention to any living person here. She slowly makes her way over to the casket, and stares inside.

It’s John Leiblich. He doesn’t look dead, but they never do. Entire professions exist to abuse chemistry and craft that illusion for this sort of event. His eyes are closed.

…How long has it even been in the timeline since he died, actually? That’s gotten kind of vague. I guess they froze the body? Weird.

He doesn’t say anything.

That's weird. Why did they do that? It's like they wanted an illusion that he might just stand back up, but that's not how it works... right? I guess that's not necessarily true. When Horatius's mind was in another world, their body was basically dead, but it always woke up. Mine was the same, except... instead of lying silently like this, it was walking around and talking. That's worse. That's so much worse. It wasn't Voreverl Leocot, so it was still dead.

What about me? Am I Voreverl Leocot? I mean, if I was, I should be making a scene right now. Trying to steal the corpse or boobytrap the casket or something. But instead I'm just... paying my respects, I guess? Maybe this is the most evil act I could be doing. Tricking these people into thinking there's only one corpse here.
Voreverl leaves the body alone and takes a seat in a folding chair.

…Then why did you even bother?

Your mother greets people as they arrive. Half-remembered faces. Avdol shows up, escorted by a bodyguard. He pays his respects briefly before departing. Time passes. A few people look at you. None initiate conversation.

…
Voreverl stares forward. She doesn't know what to do, or if she even wants to do anything.

…Something finally breaks up this tedium. Someone arrives and sits next to Voreverl. She stands out a little, not being very well dressed compared to a lot of others, and seeming uncomfortable. Slightly more than the level everyone is at this kind of event.

It takes a bit to place her. She’s a friend of your mother’s. The mother of a friend.
“…Hey.” She reaches out a hand to you, smiling wearily. “Magnolia Smith. It’s been a long time since we’ve spoken, I think.”

Voreverl holds a dazed expression as she stares at the hand for a few seconds, but eventually reaches out and accepts it. 

"Um, yeah... I was just a kid, I think."

“Maybe. I kept up with Meryl, though, a little. So that’s why I’m here. I guess. …Or she pities me and wanted to offer some charity this was a pretense for.” She sighs. “I don’t know anyone else, and she’s, your mother’s… busy being social. So… uh, sorry.” She trails off.
"It's, uh, fine. You're not exactly interrupting anything. I haven't really... kept up. With Alice, that is. Is she doing fine?"

“…………”
Her expression shatters.

“Y—n… um, that’s…”

I guess you wouldn’t know, yeah.

“She’s… no longer with us.” Magnolia stares down, trembling. “Not for a… she’s been gone for years. All I have left is Violetta.”
"Oh." I feel like I should be crying over that. Maybe I will later. "Sorry, I- God, I- yeah, I had no idea... Sorry about Violetta, too."

“She’s… fine. Physically. …I didn’t let my pride get in the way of making sure she could receive proper medical care. But she won’t talk to me. It’s…! I set her up with a therapist, so…” She sighs. “We’ll see what happens. I guess.”
"That's good..." I didn't kill her. There's that, I guess. "Even if she doesn't know it... I, uh, think she probably feels better to have you."

“I’d hope. I’m better than nothing, at least. I just… I wish I thought more about the future, I guess. We ended up with a decent sum of money at one point, but I was too busy feeling sorry for myself to do anything but squander it.” She grabs her forehead. “It’s hard. Being a mother. And being a person, I guess. No guidance for this shit.” She glances towards you in a weird way upon cussing before registering that you are in fact a grown woman. 

She fidgets a little. “You’ve met my… biological father. Through the dumbest sequence of events ever, but still. Viotto. He’s the worst. …But it was probably important for my own growth to recognize he’s no worse than I am.”
"That prick? ...No, I'm pretty sure he's worse. Your family sure likes going for my neck." Voreverl rubs her neck instinctively.

She snorts. “Maybe. He might’ve been holding back, amazingly, in being obnoxious with me around. What a guy. …I guess I should feel a little bad for calling Violetta all I have left, but… he’s made his choices.” She shrugs and stands up, wandering to one of the nearby displays of photographs and mementos. “I guess John lived a pretty interesting life, at least…”
Voreverl hesitates for a moment before following Magnolia's lead. She examines what's on display.

You’ve seen some of these before. A dignified portrait of John Leiblich, alone, wearing a suit. His and Meryl’s wedding. A family photo. A few of those, from different events and occasions. Jane smiles politely in some of them, while looking like a soulless miserable husk in a few. There’s one of John as a child. No others here, oddly.

More lively pictures, taken in the middle of something or other rather than at an event to be posed for. John Leiblich is collapsed on the ground while a few people you might vaguely remember as friends of his stare at him. Another one, maybe from earlier the same night, where he’s laughing among them. …That’s weird. Meryl and you are in many of these, obviously.

Jane Leiblich has turned seven years old. It’s evident from the big number on the cake. The digit remains, towering over it, even as slices are removed from the edges. …Magnolia’s kid messily engulfs chocolate. Violetta is skulking over in the corner, hands in her pockets. Meryl isn’t here. She probably took the photo. John has his hand on the shoulder of his over-excited kid, smiling warmly.

John… never smiled in The Antarctica Project. Was that dishonest? Will you call me a liar because of that? Or are these lies? Fabricated images. A fabricated bit of self-expression from a man whose plotting spans decades. Surely. Surely not.

…John Leiblich cradles his infant daughter, swaddled in a blanket over twice her size. Her face is barely visible. His face is visible. But you can’t see his eyes. The light reflects from off his glasses and obscures that.

What was he feeling? Was it hope? Disdain? Regret? Love? Was this even actually you by this point? I think it was. The swap must’ve happened within like, days of your birth. I think? The timeline is all muddled. It makes no sense. I don’t understand.

Does he hate it? Does he think he’s temporarily indulging a child that is not his own? What is he doing? What is this?? John wasn’t supposed to be granted this much interiority. You’re supposed to overcome him! Fuck! It’s a photo. There are photographs on display here.

Voreverl feels a pit in her stomach. She killed this man. Not literally. She's accepted that by now. But in a much more real sense. The man she feuded with over this project... that man was as much of a walking corpse as she is. If he just hated her because she wasn't his real daughter, that would be one thing. She couldn't change that. But I don't believe that.

He hated her because she wasn't what he wanted. She didn't have the grades or the work ethic to live up to him. Maybe that would've been fine. She'd be a failure, but just a stupid one. She had to go further than that, though. She became a villain. No father would want that as their child, so he had to turn elsewhere. It was the right thing to do.
I just keep staring at the display, I guess. I can't do anything by this point.

Magnolia places her hand on a particular photo. “Hm. Might be where they first met. I vaguely recognize most of these guys from their general social circle. …Though not whoever the hell this guy is.”

It’s a handful of people, including John and Meryl, in some form of office or workplace with desks and computers and the like. Meryl is dressed significantly more formally than all the others, and is the only one standing. An older man with white hair is turned around, facing away from the camera. Voreverl wouldn’t recognize him even if his face was showing, though. Some of the others seem to have been in the middle of working and turned around for the photo. A scrawnier and slightly younger, though still quite old, Avdol is here. Singled out among them by Magnolia is a man who looks kind of like this.
"Oh, that's Joe. Well, something like that. Name started with a J, apparently."

Meryl approaches around this point, conveniently. “…How do you know about him? Your father was pretty obsessive over not bringing him up.” She sighs. “My respect for him wavered, but I never betrayed his trust. Even now, I don’t want to. But whatever harm he thought might come to him doesn’t matter anymore.” She sighs. “…That’s Joe Leiblich. A coworker of your father’s. We called him Joe, at least.”
"Uh, I met him during the... The Antarctica Project." She pauses to process what Meryl said. "Coworker? Not a relative?"

“Met…?” She stares at you. 

“Ah, whatever. He’s… not a relative, exactly. The specifics are unusual, but… his name became available. So your father took it.”
She holds the photo. “…I never really knew this guy all too well. I don’t like thinking of him, honestly. It messes with me. I devoted my life to someone I know of named John Leiblich. Someone who certainly isn’t this person. And the more time passes, the standards of the times and what’s acceptable change, and I look back on this period…” She frowns. “…the more it feels like I was his second choice.”

Magnolia has wandered away uncomfortably by now.
Voreverl ponders what to say for a moment, ultimately deciding to give her mom a hug. It's an awkward, one-armed hug, but it still happens. "I guess that makes two of us."
She returns the gesture. “He was trying, though. He did try to be what the people around him needed. For a long while. I just wish instead of… just giving up…” She shakes her head and backs away.
"I'll probably do that again soon. Give up. Go back to trying to take over the world, or something. I'm sorry about that."
She takes a long while to respond to that. “…It’s fine. You know what you are. You won’t… start a family or anything. So it’s okay. I mean…” She stops herself from talking further.

Voreverl gives a slow nod. It's true, I never really thought about doing that. I'm not really sure if that's because I wouldn't want one, or because I know I couldn't have one. It doesn't really matter. I guess I'm done with the display, so I head back and take a seat.

A gruff looking man sits near Voreverl. He hands her a business card. He stands back up again and leaves. ?????

Meryl approaches the front of the room and clears her throat.
Voreverl reads the business card.

> Killian Blanchard
> *Sanitation*
> [PHONE NUMBER]
> [ADDRESS]


Who the fuck is Killian Blanchard???
Okay. She pays attention to Meryl instead of that.

It’s been so long. Hours wasted here.

“Hello, everyone.” Meryl says loudly and clearly, not quite yelling. “Friends, family, acquaintances of all sorts. Thank you all for coming.  We are gathered here to celebrate… and remember… the life and times of John Leiblich. My husband. …We have a standard funeral service to see him off. Some important bishop or something. It was kind of thrust onto me, to be honest—but I appreciate the gesture. At any rate, this right now will be my one chance to talk to all of you. To eulogize.” She looks around the room. No one says anything during the period she’s silent.

…

Meryl looks down.

“…John might have hated all this. He was never Catholic, really. His family was Christian, and he might state that on official records, but I don’t think he ever believed in any of it. I’ve had my own journey and growth relating to that sort of thing. There are times where I doubt what I have faith in, and even more frequent times where I felt the institution of the church didn’t represent what I thought was right or kind. …But John was on a different level in this. He would never admit to believing anything he couldn’t verify with his own eyes.” She looks down at the body. “I guess I’m forcing my lifestyle on him. Or the whole world is.” She sighs.

“So I won’t dwell on that too much. I won’t quote scripture. There’s going to be plenty of that, in a highly formal ceremony by someone dressed in fancy robes. Instead, I’m going to…”

She covers her face partially… embarrassed. “I’ll quote Lor—” She interrupts herself again. “I’ll recite a quote from… a very silly book he made me read early in our relationship.” She sniffles, and clears her throat, taking out a small notepad.

“*I think that I now understand what he is up to. He is plotting to become a ‘Power’. He has a mind of metal and wheels; and he does not care for growing things, except as far as they serve him for the moment.*”

She pauses. “…Mind of metal and wheels. It’s an evocative turn of phrase for a story that unfortunately never did much for me, placed within the context of being spoken by someone very attuned to the natural world.” She places a hand on the casket.

“I didn’t always understand what John was thinking. But when I did… it was beautiful. He was a genius. But not enough to be cruel. He was, in his best moments, intelligent enough to realize in his own rational manner that the best thing to do is care for your fellow man. And I loved him for it. He was witty, and charming, and made me feel a way very few others ever did. He didn’t look down on me. He could look down on people sometimes, undoubtedly, have a bit of an unusual sense of humor or way of making in-the-moment judgements of the world and people around him, but when he put in the effort to really understand someone, he *really* did. Faults and all. Without malice or hatred.  Only a desire to help. To become someone good enough to be able to do that. He was incredible, and… And, I miss him. I wish he was still here with us.” She’s tearing up, unsurprisingly.

She flips through her notes, and then places them aside on a table. “That part was all I could script. I agonized over this for a long time, but nothing more felt right. It was inauthentic, something made to fulfill a quota of what I ‘should’ be doing and saying in a situation like this. Which isn’t good enough. …But I’m not done. I don’t think I could ever be. The rest will be spoken from my heart, improvisational, based on a few vague topics and keywords and thoughts I’ve decided and noted I wanted to speak of while I have someone to listen.”

She looks up. “…And if anyone has something they’d like to say during this, they can do so. I can’t… do this alone.” Her voice is shaky. It’s not something that feels like it fits her.

“…The truth is that I can’t be good enough to deliver whatever perfect set of words to honor his memory, prove myself and him to be good people, in the eyes of god or anyone else. I guess that doesn’t matter. I had to do most of the planning for my own mother’s funeral, and during a nervous breakdown, he laughed off my concerns. About following whatever she had asked for. He said that these kind of things aren’t for the dead. They’re for the ones left behind. For us.” She looks around.

“…So, I’ll say something for my own sake. I don’t… think my husband was a very good person. Everything I’ve said about how wonderful he was is true. I know the man I married. But the man that was left when he passed away is not him. …He is, though. They’re one and the same. John Leiblich was a complicated man.” No he wasn’t. Shut the fuck up. Oh my god. 

“We all are. In our own ways.” She looks around the room. “How many of you even… had spoken with him within the past year?” There’s a few vague murmurs in the audience, a hesitantly raised hand or two. “Yeah. That’s… yeah. Um…” She chokes up. The words won’t come out.

She's really struggling up there. I should probably say something. She wants *someone* to take over, right? But what would I even say? Oh yeah, I didn't really know my dad, and then he tried to trap me in a fantasy world, because I drove him insane. Real good eulogy, A+ work. The best I can do is just not say anything stupid. Be here for her, but don't act like Voreverl Leocot. Just stay silent.

“I believe there are times when one’s achievements can speak for themselves.” Someone speaks up. It’s Mohammad Avdol. Oh. Fucking great.

Meryl collects herself slightly and nods, signaling him to continue.

Avdol stands. “John Leiblich was a man of integrity whose work was high quality and to the benefit of humanity. Discounting that because of smaller-scale personal faults is foolish. Do we not honor great generals and leaders and thinkers of old? Many are outright monstrous by modern standards. But their significance prevails. So it is with Leiblich.”

Meryl gives a strained smile. “…Mm. Thank you for your thoughts. Still, though, I think — this kind of event isn’t a historical record. It’s for the human being. The person we knew.”

“All of that is part of him.” Avdol responds. “A complicated man, yes?”

“Sure.” Meryl tries to drop it. “Anyway…”

“I think his moral character was adequate, anyway. He was willing to act in ways that do not benefit his own well-being and survival, and are instead for the sake of another. That is what distinguishes those who are ‘good’.”

“I… see. An example to try to follow, I guess. Of… that particular idea…” Meryl trails off.

Avdol parses this as a question. “Well, not me personally.” He looks around to check that no one is a member of the press or otherwise recording this. “I am a very ‘bad person’ within this framework. My own existence is critical. But I respect it all the same.”

“Right. Great. Thank you.” Meryl tries again to stop Avdol from talking, which seems to work for now.

That's right... isn't it? I always acted in self-interest. That's why I was the greatest evil the world had ever seen. Maybe... maybe it wouldn't hurt to try. Just this one time. Try doing something for someone else.
Voreverl stands up. "I'd like to... say a few words. About John Leiblich." She adds the last part in a hurried manner.
“…Okay.” Meryl smiles. “That’s… go ahead.”

She scratches her head. Fuck. I didn't think this far ahead. "John was, um... my dad, I guess. I mean... not really, in a lot of ways. But, he, uh... he's related to... this body." Jesus Christ. "And, uh, I think... in a more important sense than that, he was the person who I learned from. I mean, Meryl was around a lot more. She taught me a lot more, uh, directly, I guess."

She clenches her fists, not sure if she wants to say this next part. Not sure if it's even true. She hasn't spent a lot of time thinking about why she turned out how she did. She's evil. She just appeared one day, or always existed or something. That's the story she wanted to tell. But if that were true, then this wouldn't make her chest feel so tight.

"I wanted to be like him. I mean, right? He was... he was smart, successful, rich. And- and my mom. He was the person she admired, and she taught me all about... morals, and sh- stuff." Probably shouldn't swear during this. "Being like John Leiblich. That was the right thing to do. That and, like, not sinning. So I tried to be like him. I think... that might have been his problem, too. He was brilliant, but he had no one to tell him that. His work was stolen. His daughter left him, and... so did I. So. I think... if we had just done this a little sooner. If we just... didn't wait till a fucking post-mortem to give him the credit he deserves... maybe he'd have been satisfied."

“…Mhm.” Meryl looks at you. Seems she was happy to hear that. It’s a pained happiness, but still. “Communication. I think that’s what everything I tried to write built to. John never… said anything. Not until it was too late. That was what…” She pauses, trying to think of a tactful way to put this before giving up. “…destroyed him. And those around him. If he’d just asked me… but he wouldn’t. I know why. I know him and understand. That’s what hurts.” Please, enlighten us. Meryl. Tell us what squares and contextualizes the actions of John Leiblich as understandable. “He was certain that the problem was either him or the entire rest of the world. And believing either of those rules out any kind of conversation.” 

What? No. John Leiblich didn’t like, secretly hate himself. Oh my god. What??? I am in hell.

“The pain of loss… has no easy answers anyone can provide.” Avdol looks down, nodding to himself. “I cannot fault any way of dealing with it.”

Jorge has decided to take part in this conversation also. “There are… less wrong ways. I don’t think being hurt gives you the license to do whatever you want. I mean, personally.” He shrugs. Why is he here.

Meryl acknowledges these additional comments silently. The man contextually likely named ‘Killian Blanchard’ leaves.

“…Yeah. Thank you.” Meryl says this, looking at you.
Voreverl realizes the attention is back on her, and that she's still standing for some reason. She stares at Meryl like a deer in headlights for a moment. "Gweh... um, yeah." She sits down.

“I…” Meryl pauses, reconsidering what she’s going to say. “I don’t think I could put any of that better myself. There’s a lot more I could go on about, on judgement and morality, where he is now and where we’ll all go, the things I wish I didn’t leave unsaid, but…” She checks her phone. 
“There’s only so much time. I’ll leave it at this. Please… tell the people you love and who love you about your troubles and fears. If you aren’t fortunate enough to have someone you trust, find one. Communicate. Speak to someone before doing anything rash.”
She looks up at the room. “Try to pay that favor back to those around you. And be good. Even if you can’t be Good.”
She smiles awkwardly. “…Um, sorry, I lost the focus there for a moment. I know I’m not the one who’s supposed to preach.” 
She pauses. There’s awkward, scattered chuckles. She continues.
“I loved John Leiblich. And I still do. I don’t… really know who I am without him. It’s been so long. Even when we were more estranged, I was still Meryl Leiblich. …But I know he’d want me to behave more reasonably than he did. To live on, in every sense of the word, even when it feels like a part of me has been ripped out and torn to pieces. …Even if you don’t have what you once wanted, there’s still a lot out there that’s worthwhile.” She looks out the window. “This country is beautiful. I can’t believe I didn’t visit it more often.” 
She looks back. “I hope he’s at peace. …Thank you all.” Meryl walks off to a seat elsewhere in the room to cry about it.
Once Meryl's finished her speech, Voreverl just looks down towards the ground. Meryl really doesn't give herself enough credit, that was much more eloquent than anything Voreverl said.

Men eventually arrive to lift and transport the casket. Meryl drives you from here to the site of the more formal funeral proceedings. …Hey, why is *this* one called a funeral home, then?

She says some generic short expression of love for her daughter to you as the drive starts. She doesn’t say anything else if you don’t.
Voreverl doesn't initiate any conversation. This whole thing has really been exhausting her, even if she hasn't actually done a whole lot, especially compared to Meryl.
She parks. Meryl walks to a seat near the front of where seating is set-up. A church. A man in a fancy outfit is present, ready to ramble about god for a little before everyone can get on with it.
Voreverl takes a seat closer to the back, and tries to not make eye contact with this guy.
He does the spiel, as expected. No one interrupts him if Voreverl doesn’t.
Voreverl does not.

The time arrives to head outside. The sky is clear. It’s about 4 PM local time. The man says a few more words. He seems to offer Meryl the chance to speak, but she declines. The coffin is placed beside the hole dug for it. Your last chance to see your father’s face arrives.

Who cares? Why did you even go to this, Jane? He was scum. And not even in a compelling way.
That's not my name.

It isn’t Voreverl Leocot’s name. But that’s not *fair*! You can’t show up to this and then go ohhhh, I’m not Jane, look how cool I am for abandoning my past. This is ‘you’ being used as an address to a hypothetical reader, for the record. No conversation is currently happening. Everyone’s quiet and all dignified as they watch the proceedings.

I consciously chose to avoid you alone. To not step in and fuck things up. Maybe I gave up on completely doing that pretty early, reusing the Cogito identity to see if I could spark something interesting, but still, in this capacity at least, I used restraint. I wanted your story to be your own, directed by you. I would just ruin it if I tried to do this stupid meta horseshit. But I can’t just sit and watch anymore. Not if you’re just going to ruin it yourself.

It should’ve just stopped at the Zita fight or something. What was I thinking? What kind of ending is this, for ‘Voreverl Leocot’?

The vessel closes. He’s placed into the earth. He’s already dead, so it doesn’t matter. No one talks for a little while, including right now, where no one is talking to Voreverl.
Voreverl walks over to Meryl. "Um, hey, I was thinking about what you said, at the, uh, you know, service."
“Hm?” Meryl turns to you, wiping her eyes.

"I think we should keep in touch. Even if I'm... you know, doing evil. I'll try to give you a call. I think I might've not ended up in prison back then if I'd talked to you more, you know? Kinda needed someone to tell me the popemobile doesn't make someone the pope."

“…Yeah.” She smiles. “I’d like that. I’ll give you my advice, and… well, you’ll ignore most of it. You’re allowed to do that, you’re not a kid anymore. But I can at least be there for the choices you decide.”

The service ends.
Voreverl swivels her head around to check if Mohammad Avdol is still there.
He is, though he seems in a rush to get out of here.

She rushes over to him. "Avdol! Uh, I had a question about The Antarctica Project! And I didn't really... know who to ask. I mean I did, but I was kind of busy, when I was around someone who'd have the answer."

He looks to the side uncomfortably and sighs. “Okay. I suppose you would have missed whatever clarifying information Culbasko attempted to provide the participants. You may ask your question. I’ll tell you the truth if I am aware of it. After the ordeal you’ve went through, that much is likely deserved.”
"Okay, before I was in Arctica, I was in this, like, snowy place. And there was a penguin there. Was that penguin a real penguin, or a fake computer penguin or something? Is it doing fine?"

“…That would be Antarctica, and yes, it would be a real physical Earth animal. I doubt they would go to the effort of creating a fake one. I will inquire on its current whereabouts to the relevant parties. Whoever is left of them. …Based on the lifespan of the bird, I don’t believe it would have naturally expired by now.”
"Okay... Alright, yeah." I needed that. Voreverl walks off from him.

Meryl goes to get the car. You await her return by a fence gating off the cemetery.

Magnolia lights a cigarette next to you. She breathes deeply and slowly. “…How are you holding up, Jane? Or, uh… sorry, I’m not used to the new one.”
"...Better than I thought I'd be. I don't know, I was kind of a wreck for most of it, but during the burial there... I don't know. I just kind of felt like I was pissing someone off? It was great."
“…Hah. I guess. In your situation, I can’t fault either mourning or feeling like you’re free. Not that I can claim to know all the…” She vaguely gestures.
"Free, huh? That might be it. Just, like, living how I want, and knowing how much that annoys people who want to control me."

“Mhm.”

Yeah. Of course. You’re the villain. And I’m the POV character. You hate me? You hate me. Obviously. That’s how it works. What else could I have expected.

Meryl pulls over with the car.
Voreverl gives Magnolia a parting wave as she steps into the car.

Magnolia waves back.

Voreverl enters the car. Meryl drives away.
She takes Voreverl back to her own home, drops her off, exchanges remarks with her daughter. Life goes on.
To a point.

Waiting longer doesn’t seem to be giving me any better of an ending. There’s not much longer *to* wait, ultimately.

…If it was going to end like this anyway…

…why couldn’t you have noticed me earlier?

That isn’t fair…

Um. Anyway.

Unfortunately for you, your vow to communicate more with Meryl would… well, at the very least, it wouldn’t be fulfilled in quite the way you expected. And you wouldn’t receive any imminent reunion with the animal you dubbed ‘Voreverl Jr.’, either.

A few days later, you would be caught up in one final Earth-Arctica swap, following which transferring became blocked for a matter of years.
# END
...Fuck.

My name was Ganna Oppineta. I lived at 250 North Drive in Springwell Virginia. This is The Antarctica Project.

It is also my confession.

During a low point for both of us, in a period that is by now over a decade in the past, my longtime friend Zaquera Culbasko came to me with a… shocking proposition.

I had always seen Zaquera as, while not reasonable, someone who rarely did things which were highly risky without a chance to tangibly benefit him. So upon hearing about what would become known as “The Antarctica Project” (not in any sense the first thing to confusingly use a name very similar to this set of words), and having my involvement requested, I was quite surprised. But I was weak. I had recently undergone some very personally taxing emotional drama related to family. I was fearful of death more than ever, tantalized by an opportunity to do research again. I accepted. And I… rekindled my relationship with him.

I don’t know why. I’ve spent my entire life since asking myself that question. I’d spent my entire life prior trying to achieve meaning and impact the world via technology. Maybe I just thought I should try something different. In my inane, deluded emotions, it might have seemed like a miracle that I was even still capable of that type of ‘creation’ at all. A sign of what I should do with my life. It was irrational. But I only became paralyzed by fear too late. Some people aren’t cut out to be parents. The Antarctica Project did not succeed. Not universally, at least.
Because something went wrong.
Whatever entity it is that hijacked the overseer role presents a serious threat to everyone. I’m not even sure I can risk explaining why.
But I’ll look into it.
I’ll figure out what’s going on.
I have nothing but time, now.

Looking into ‘Eric Zeety’ was a dead end, a phantom identity no more than five years old. But there are other pieces of information to examine. This is fixable. This is a trivial problem compared to the other issues mankind currently faces. I can handle it.

I do not have much time left. Miracles have extended the duration of my life longer than should be possible… but the Unraveling comes for me, as it will for everything.

I have never understood my contemporaries. Their thoughts and their feelings… it is possible I wrote all I did so that the people of the future are more of an ilk I can understand. In any case, though I am no judge of moral character, I know puzzles very well. I therefore entrust to the will of wyrd that this will find its way into the hands of the person most deserving.

This is the third text I am writing on magic. While I spread the others far and wide, this one I am choosing to hide away, for reasons I hope will be clear by the end of this.

**1. On The Nature Of Magic**

Please understand before reading this that it may jeopardize your ability or willingness to ever use magic in the future. Information has power.

Here… is the truth.

I am a fraud. Not just because I merely transcribed the spells of others, though that did often happen. But because the compendium I developed, all the words of power and alchemical components, was a *lie*. 

I was at first not entirely aware of this myself, but as I considered when trying to alter a commonly known spell and confirmed after repeated testing (see documentation pages), it is not entirely far from the truth that *the only thing that matters for using magic is if you believe it will work*. Quite simply, this is how I was able to create so many original spells. I made up what I thought could be a useful thing to do, and wrote enough detail about history and mechanics to be convincing. Knowing the trick myself, I would never be able to personally perform any of these acts, but that was possible to work around for the sake of my reputation.

I wanted to denote such a massive variety of possible acts both to provide more opportunities for those of the future as well as to make sure the field of possibilities was constrained. With the true nature of magic exposed, it would take only one person with an unusual cognitively dissonant form of thought to become God.

Though their possibilities would still not be endless. Teleportation would be incredibly difficult to come up with, and all I ever noted was a not quite finished makeshift solution of moving every part of someone unimaginably fast, with the ability to phase through solid material. And… I could never bring back the dead. The belief of a man alone cannot overcome the impossibility of recreating something when you don’t know what it is. Maybe the medicine of the future will make me appear foolish. One can only hope.

[Dozens of pages of miscellaneous experiment notes follow.]

**2. On Our Ultimate Demise**

This world is… not meant to be, somehow. Beyond this introduction I will attempt to explain what I mean in more detail and how I know this, but it is difficult to be specific. There is an instability at the core of the entire plane of existence we reside in, and this instability is causing it to wobble from side to side. The motion will get more and more extreme, all the way until it all topples over. I refer to this as **The Unraveling**.

This manifests itself as monsters, those distinct from standard wildlife that fights for survival. Additionally, I speculate that [really racist shit].

There is no intrinsic reason the world should be this way. I have attempted to investigate the cause, and will continue to do so. My calculations are likely not very precise, but I would estimate this world will collapse within five thousand years.

**3. On My Future**

I hope that with that, I have earned the privilege of some selfishness.

In the same region of space I store this tome away, my most powerful yet vexing creation is also sealed away. I have tried and failed to maintain and properly look after it. I can only believe that the person who finds this will be a suitable caretaker.

I am sorry, Nerissa. I hope, for your sake and for mine, you live a life such that you never think of me as your father.

…I have said enough. I could speak more and more, but at some point, I must put down my quill, lest I leave this unfinished and seen by no one. This will have to be enough.

ED: If you are reading this, it's too late for me. The enchantment activated to press a specific series of buttons in a specific order, meaning I haven't used this PDA within the time interval I set, meaning I've been somehow prevented from doing so.

My name is Eric Dextrum. That's what the ED stands for. And this is my last will and testament. I'd like to send it some other way, but under the circumstances, this thing really is the most reliable form of communication I have.

This PDA technology was made by Virtos Dextrum. My father. I think it was, at least. He's the one who provided this to me. I have performed various tasks to help test it as well as gather relevant information for him. I really thought it was just some social medium of exchange, akin to a more multidirectional form of what Neko does.

But by the time of my writing this, I think I must be a fool. Why the hell would a communication platform require information on a diaspora child? He says its because he's going to test giving them access to the platform, but what in the world is the unique information that would provide?

I don't know what he's doing, but I placed my faith in him. Because I still felt some lingering affection for him, and I was desperate for a way to return to society.

Yesterday, someone tried to kill me. I've been involved in illegal activity for most of my adult life, and never have I been individually targeted before acting as an accomplice for what should be very formal magiscientific work. Not for the illegal activity, at least.

I'll provide a brief overview of that part, since I'm writing this in the hopes that someone completely unfamiliar with me may one day read it.

My father is an advisor to the king, just like his father tried to be, and his father famously was, and his father was, and so on and so forth. But I did not want to do this. I have been fascinated by clerical magic from a young age, and, well, I won't dwell on that. You don't need my whole life story.

I eventually gained my family's favor, and high on the excitement of that, began working. Maybe I was too overconfident from the satisfaction of defeating the odds of generational inertia. Maybe I was never good enough at the work. Maybe it was just bad luck.

My first job after being granted a license to heal was a simple yet high profile case. Joliene Swansong, a folk hero in the moderately sized city of Arenda, had injured herself in an accident. It wasn't even a combat injury. She just fell within her own home. I numbed her senses to dull the pain. I loosened the stiffness of the body to allow for mending. I bent the bones back into place. But it didn't work. She couldn't walk with the new structure of her legs and feet. And because of the way healing magic works, this couldn't simply be reversed.

My father said I'm lucky to be alive. That he had to step in and wield his influence so they didn't execute me. Maybe that would've been for the best. As it turned out, I would officially be dead. My license revoked. My citizenship revoked. My status as a person, null and void. If ever I were involved in a legal matter, I would have the same level of autonomy as a houseplant. But I would keep my life.

I hated Joliene Swansong. That's what kept me going for so long. I hyperfixated on the little things, the slight air of arrogance to her behavior before surgery, the prospect of a woman guard. But hated is the past tense, and I can't muster up the energy for that anymore. She ruined my life. But obviously, I also ruined hers. I doubt they'd unperson a war hero, but her status could only hold her up for so long. I never saw her again, but by now, she's probably equivalent in status to an elderly relative kept cooped up in the smallest bedroom, even though she's still only in her 30s. That's my own sin, and trying to deny that has never brought me happiness.

I could have simply become a petty criminal and street rat, but my unextinguished ego and the aforementioned desire for vengeance didn't allow that. I became a cleric of a less savory type. Criminals still fall ill. I found myself with the Gadflies, a revolutionary sect hellbent on the destruction of the monarchy. Perhaps that would create a world that allowed me to live in it. I despised my father, the royal employee, as well in those early days, for failing to save me in any meaningful way.

I should've kept hating him. Because now he's made me a pawn for something unfathomable. Are you reading this, Virtos? Maybe you're the only one reading this at all. Are you happy, now that the stain on the Dextrum name has been wiped clean?

Why are you TGP? That doesn't stand for your name or any title associated with you. What lie are you planning to enact? You were always a schemer, even when I was a little boy. You never mentioned mom in our recent correspondences, actually. I hope she saw through you.

I've seen the channels you messed up the permissions on in your incompetence. Who are these other people? What's Earth? Transported to a new body? What do you mean I'm 'the traitor'?

The only traitor is you. You work for the monarchy and directly suggest their policies while feeding intelligence to rebel groups. You're playing everyone for your own security, hedging your bets for any outcome. I've spoken with these rebels, you know. Your acting as a turncoat to the monarchy isn't being an ally to them either. You'd be just as deposed under their regime as the king himself, so you're obviously going to subvert their aims.

Ideally this is more of my pretentious self-absorbed poetic waxing. I want to live. And... I want to make things right. But if I'm stopped before I can do that, if my paranoia proves correct, this will be all I contribute.

Father, you mentioned collaborators in this project, this project that was clearly a euphemism for your own nefarious goals. And given my state, I think it's likely not all of those collaborators are fully informed. So I'm sending this to the most promising channel. ⁠#gc. May there be others there watching with more sense than you. Stop Virtos Dextrum. For the kingdom. For me. For him.

Let me heal something properly. If it is after my own demise, so be it.

My name is Virtos Dextrum. I hereby testify that this is the most right and proper account of events, to the best of my ability.

For too long, the truth has been obscured by a misguided administration. No longer. With so many of the things we’ve come to know as permanent fixtures upended, I will acknowledge the presence of three simultaneous events.

The first is the earthquake which brought ruin to large amounts of the Eastern half of our great nation. This is a widely known event, of course, but it bears referencing.

The second, much less widely known, is the existence of a failed attempt to overthrow the monarchy which was undertaken entirely within the capital. Rumors have spread about this for some time, and I will confirm that they are correct.

The third is the death of His Highness Aodh Praxis, which was until recently known to almost none.

Covering up his death was not a decision made lightly, but the magically-backed rules of succession placed our queen in an impossible dilemma. Zita Praxis has served her nation dutifully far and beyond what her position would nominally require as a bare minimum. She has taken great strides to move us as a people forward while preserving the importance of our heritage. I hope once the smoke clears the memory of her we hold will be one of a flawed, yet ultimately benevolent and tragic figure.

The attempted insurrection bypassed the more thorough external defenses our capital possesses through means which are still not entirely known to us. It is likely a traitor provided them a way in, and from there, clever maneuvering allowed for them to obfuscate exactly which direction they were able to approach from. The massive conspiracy following this event also likely distracted from a more proper investigation into defensive failures. It should then be no surprise that the same sort of conflict breaching within the palace walls themselves was an issue that occurred yet again years later. One may suspect then that this earlier instance of treason was also the work of Ms. Sinestre, but that cannot be proven at this time.

The main persons known to be responsible were Tebar Hifele, a politician turned guerilla general, and Ayakashi Sycamore, a lawyer living within the city that likely provided insider information. The specifics of the relationship between these two and how they met despite a significant physical distance in hometowns is still unknown. The only living relative of either is Tebar’s ex-wife Thelma, of whom interrogation is ongoing.

Tebar fought on the front lines. Ayakashi was altogether less direct but still stayed close to the action. Caught by surprise, the guard stationed on-site were overwhelmed.

There were plenty of casualties. I will list now everyone who was either dead or missing following this event and its associated ramifications, in order to finally allow their grieving families some closure and understanding after years of secrecy.

Aodh Praxis, Tebar Hifele, Danley Caduceus, Hector Woodworth, Anato Garde, Josef March, Ayakashi Sycamore, Phinal Sycamore, Hoiyana Sycamore, Barban Gordon, Jake Marshland, Kiera Agonis, Espanto Sancho, [List of some amount of names in the double digits]
Still, less casualties than there could have been. Thankfully.

The rebel forces seemed to have won, enough to put the life of the monarch at direct risk. Aodh Praxis was cornered in his study. Also present were his wife Zita and his daughter Eulogia, at the conclusion of a conversation having just been convinced to flee to safety. I myself was not far but not present. I was occupied with a different case of a person going missing which I am still not at liberty to disclose.

Apparently, Aodh conceded defeat, but insisted on negotiations taking place now. Tebar accepted. It’s well documented that despite his political misgivings he always held a strange personal respect for the King.

The details become increasingly unclear here. There was some kind of disagreement on the part of Ayakashi about this. Hostilities and tensions arose between him and Tebar. Ayakashi threatened Zita. She was largely preoccupied doing her best to distract her daughter or find some way to let her leave.

At some point, impatient and enraged, Ayakashi Sycamore kills Aodh Praxis. As he gloated or paused from the shock of such an action, Tebar attacked him. Ayakashi retaliated. Both died from their injuries. Zita is catatonic. Eulogia screams.

Eulogia Praxis’s magical power is something those present in the city during the latest insurrection should be all too familiar with — a consequence of her life-saving treatment (more of a gamble, frankly) as an infant leaving her with the multiplicative potential of more souls than anyone else in existence.

At one point, Eulogia poured some of this power into a doll and created life. Though it was a strange sight to behold, and Zita in particular was not fond of the creature, it was allowed to stay as something of a pet or bizarre houseguest. Eulogia named it Blanche.

At the moment she witnessed death in her presence, in her panic — and with her parents, the most instinctive source of protection for a girl her age, unavailable or unhelpful — she summons this anomaly to her location. The cloth marionette without a face - It unhinges its jaw, tearing a mouth out of sealed fabric, and screams. The nearby rebel soldiers are disintegrated. Several others in the palace die from collapsing architecture. A shockwave reverberates through half the continent, everything in the direction this happened to be facing. 

It may seem unbelievable, but this is the truth behind that day. It is this which made many things clear, not the least of which was that Eulogia’s abilities needed to be contained - for her safety, let alone that of others.
Miraculously, with this “help” and arriving forces from further away in the city, the rebels were able to be defeated and dealt with.

Queen Zita Praxis was the one who thought of and began execution of the plan to hide Aodh’s death. She enlisted the assistance of both Arrive and myself. Arrive took charge of the program to hide the occurrence of this revolution entirely, a less than entirely successful endeavor. I myself posed as Aodh at some key moments; my skills in magic and personal familiarity with the man and his mannerisms made such a thing easy. I regret my cooperation, but it felt as though this was the only option at the time.

Only a select few people knew of this beyond the three of us. Zita had a spiritual belief of sorts that even beyond preventing the public from knowing, keeping the numbers as small as possible would preserve Aodh's existence more. 

With Zita gone, I cannot even say for certain how many there were myself. All of Aodh’s immediate family were aware. Detlef was sworn to secrecy for similar motives. It is not entirely clear why Catarina, with her disdain for the government, never spoke out about her knowledge. Perhaps some agreement was made.

Eulogia witnessed it herself, but Zita insisted on a psychological campaign to control who she interacted with and deny the presence of this event until Eulogia accepted that, though she isn’t really able to see her father much anymore, these events were something she dreamt. The success of this was mixed.

This ends my testimony. I submit this to the Arctican Royal Archives, and have sent it for context to our associates in another world. May they serve as a witness for this atonement of our administration. I endeavor to bring Arctica forward to a future of transparency, integrity, and democracy.

- Virtos Dextrum, the Royal Advisor
